# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: a-theory-of-justice
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-theory-of-justice] The resultant theory was challenged and refined several times in the decades following its original publication in 1971.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-theory-of-justice] A significant reappraisal was published in the 1985 essay "Justice as Fairness" and the 2001 book *Justice as Fairness: A Restatement* in which Rawls further developed his two central principles for his discussion of justice.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-theory-of-justice] Together, they assert that society should be structured to provide the greatest possible degree of liberty to its members, limited only by the principle that one individual's liberty must not infringe upon the liberty of others.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-theory-of-justice] Secondly, inequalities – either social or economic – are only to be allowed if the worst off will be better off than they might be under an equal distribution.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-theory-of-justice] Finally, if an inequality is to be justified on the grounds of its benefits, it must not create additional barriers for those without resources to access positions of power, such as public office.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-theory-of-justice] In *A Theory of Justice,* Rawls argues for a principled reconciliation of liberty and equality that is meant to apply to the basic structure of a well-ordered society.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-theory-of-justice] Central to this effort is an account of the circumstances of justice, inspired by David Hume, and a fair choice situation for parties facing such circumstances, similar to some of Immanuel Kant's views.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-theory-of-justice] Principles of justice are sought to guide the conduct of the parties.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-theory-of-justice] These parties are recognized to face moderate scarcity, and they are neither naturally altruistic nor purely egoistic.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-theory-of-justice] They have ends which they seek to advance but prefer to advance them through cooperation with others on mutually acceptable terms.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-theory-of-justice] Rawls offers a model of a fair choice situation (the original position with its veil of ignorance) within which parties would hypothetically choose mutually acceptable principles of justice.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-theory-of-justice] Under such constraints, Rawls believes that parties would find his favoured principles of justice to be especially attractive, winning out over varied alternatives, including utilitarian and right-wing libertarian accounts.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-theory-of-justice] Rawls belongs to the social contract tradition, although he takes a different view from that of previous thinkers.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-theory-of-justice] Specifically, Rawls develops what he claims are principles of justice through the use of an artificial device or thought experiment he calls the *Original position*; in which, everyone decides principles of justice from behind a veil of ignorance.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-theory-of-justice] [N]o one knows his place in society, his class position or social status, nor does anyone know his fortune in the distribution of natural assets and abilities, his intelligence, strength, and the like.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-theory-of-justice] I shall even assume that the parties do not know their conceptions of the good or their special psychological propensities.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-theory-of-justice] The principles of justice are chosen behind a veil of ignorance.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-theory-of-justice] They are the principles that rational and free persons concerned to further their own interests would accept in an initial position of equality as defining the fundamentals of the terms of their association.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-theory-of-justice] If an individual does not know how he will end up in his own conceived society, he is likely not going to privilege any one class of people, but rather develop a scheme of justice that treats all fairly.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-theory-of-justice] In particular, Rawls claims that those in the *Original Position* would adopt two principles, the second of which is a maximin strategy which would maximize the prospects of the least well-off.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-theory-of-justice] Rawls bases his *Original Position* on a "thin theory of the good" which he says "explains the rationality underlying choice of principles in the Original Position".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-theory-of-justice] A full theory of the good follows after we derive principles from the original position.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-theory-of-justice] Rawls claims that the parties in the original position would adopt two such principles, which would then govern the assignment of rights and duties and regulate the distribution of social and economic advantages across society.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-theory-of-justice] The difference principle permits inequalities in the distribution of goods only if those inequalities benefit the worst-off members of society.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-theory-of-justice] Rawls believes that this principle would be a rational choice for the representatives in the original position for the following reason: Each member of society has an equal claim on their society's goods.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-theory-of-justice] Natural attributes should not affect this claim, so the basic right of any individual, before further considerations are taken into account, must be to an equal share in material wealth.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-theory-of-justice] What, then, could justify unequal distribution?
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-theory-of-justice] Rawls argues that inequality is acceptable only if it is to the advantage of those who are worst-off.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-theory-of-justice] The agreement that stems from the original position is both *hypothetical* and *ahistorical*.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-theory-of-justice] It is hypothetical in the sense that the principles to be derived are what the parties would, under certain legitimating conditions, agree to, not what they have agreed to.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-theory-of-justice] Rawls seeks to use an argument that the principles of justice are what *would* be agreed upon if people were in the hypothetical situation of the original position and that those principles have moral weight as a result of that.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-theory-of-justice] It is ahistorical in the sense that it is not supposed that the agreement has ever been, or indeed could ever have been, derived in the real world outside of carefully limited experimental exercises.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-theory-of-justice] Rawls modifies and develops the principles of justice throughout his book.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-theory-of-justice] The first principle is often called the *greatest equal liberty principle*.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-theory-of-justice] Rawls orders the principles of justice lexically, as follows: **1**, **2b**, **2a**.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-theory-of-justice] The *greatest equal liberty principle* takes priority, followed by the *equal opportunity principle* and finally the *difference principle*.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-theory-of-justice] The first principle must be satisfied before 2b, and 2b must be satisfied before 2a.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-theory-of-justice] The *greatest equal liberty principle* is mainly concerned with the distribution of rights and liberties.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-theory-of-justice] His position is at least in some sense egalitarian, with a provision that inequalities are allowed when they benefit the least advantaged.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-theory-of-justice] An important consequence of Rawls' view is that inequalities can actually be just, as long as they are to the benefit of the least well off.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-theory-of-justice] His argument for this position rests heavily on the claim that morally arbitrary factors (for example, the family one is born into) should not determine one's life chances or opportunities.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-theory-of-justice] Further, the just savings principle requires that some sort of material respect is left for future generations.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-theory-of-justice] Although Rawls is ambiguous about what this means, it can generally be understood as "a contribution to those coming later".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-theory-of-justice] The stipulation in 2b is lexically prior to that in 2a.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-theory-of-justice] In 1972, *A Theory of Justice* was reviewed in *The New York Times Book Review* by Marshall Cohen, who described the work as "magisterial," and suggested that Rawls' use of the techniques of analytic philosophy made the book the "most formidable" defense of the social contract tradition to date.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-theory-of-justice] Michael Sandel criticized Rawls in *Liberalism and the Limits of Justice* (1982), arguing that Rawls encourages people to think about justice while divorced from the values and aspirations that define who they are as persons and that allow people to determine what justice is.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-theory-of-justice] Susan Moller Okin wrote in *Justice, Gender, and the Family* (1989) that Rawls had provided "the most influential of all twentieth-century theories of justice", but criticized him for failing to account for the injustices and hierarchies embedded in familial relations.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-theory-of-justice] In his book *Black Rights / White Wrongs*, philosopher Charles W.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-theory-of-justice] Mills critiques the underlying assumptions of Rawls’s work as inherently white, and thus subject to glaring blind spots.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-theory-of-justice] The economist Amartya Sen has raised concerns over Rawls' emphasis on primary social goods, arguing in *Inequality Reexamined* (1992) that we should attend not only to the distribution of primary goods, but also how effectively people are able to use those goods to pursue their ends.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-theory-of-justice] Norman Daniels has wondered why health care should not be treated as a primary good, and some of his subsequent work has addressed this question, arguing for a right to health care within a broadly Rawlsian framework.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-theory-of-justice] Sen critiques and attempts to revitalize *A Theory of Justice* in *The Idea of Justice* (2009).
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-theory-of-justice] He credits Rawls for revitalizing the interest in the ideas of what justice means and the stress put on fairness, objectivity, equality of opportunity, removal of poverty, and freedom.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-theory-of-justice] However, Sen, as part of his general critique of the contractarian tradition, states that ideas about a perfectly just world do not help redress actual existing inequality.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-theory-of-justice] Sen faults Rawls for overemphasizing institutions as guarantors of justice and not considering the effects of human behaviour on the institutions' ability to maintain a just society.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-theory-of-justice] Sen believes Rawls understates the difficulty in getting everyone in society to adhere to the norms of a just society.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-theory-of-justice] He also claims that Rawls' position that there be only one possible outcome of the reflective equilibrium behind the veil of ignorance is misguided.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-theory-of-justice] In contrast to Rawls, Sen believes that multiple conflicting, yet just, principles may arise and that this undermines the multistep processes that Rawls laid out as leading to a perfectly just society.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-theory-of-justice] Cohen argued that Rawls's principles of justice are influenced by assumptions about social institutions and human behaviour.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-theory-of-justice] He maintained that a theory of justice should identify principles that are fundamentally just independently of practical considerations, and therefore contended that Rawls's account was not a theory of justice in the strict sense.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p01] The *Treatise* is a classic statement of philosophical empiricism, scepticism, and naturalism.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p01] In the introduction Hume presents the idea of placing all science and philosophy on a novel foundation: namely, an empirical investigation into human nature.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p01] Impressed by Isaac Newton's achievements in the physical sciences, Hume sought to introduce the same experimental method of reasoning into the study of human psychology, with the aim of discovering the "extent and force of human understanding".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p01] Against the philosophical rationalists, Hume argues that the passions, rather than reason, cause human behaviour.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p01] He introduces the famous problem of induction, arguing that inductive reasoning and our beliefs regarding cause and effect cannot be justified by reason; instead, our faith in induction and causation is caused by mental habit and custom.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p01] Isaiah Berlin wrote of Hume that "no man has influenced the history of philosophy to a deeper or more disturbing degree".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p01] Jerry Fodor wrote of Hume's *Treatise* that it is "the foundational document of cognitive science".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p01] However, the public in Britain at the time did not agree, nor in the end did Hume himself agree, reworking the material in both *An Enquiry Concerning Human Understanding* (1748) and *An Enquiry Concerning the Principles of Morals* (1751).
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p01] Regarding *An Enquiry Concerning the Principles of Morals*, Hume said it is "of all my writings, historical, philosophical, or literary, incomparably the best".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Hume's introduction presents the idea of placing all science and philosophy on a novel foundation: namely, an empirical investigation into human psychology.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] But since the truth "must lie very deep and abstruse" where "the greatest geniuses" have not found it, careful reasoning is still needed.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] According to Hume, knowledge of "the extent and force of human understanding,... the nature of the ideas we employ, and... the operations we perform in our reasonings" is needed to make real intellectual progress.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] So he hopes "to explain the principles of human nature", thereby "propos[ing] a compleat system of the sciences, built on a foundation almost entirely new, and the only one upon which they can stand with any security".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] But an *a priori* psychology would be hopeless: the science of man must be pursued by the experimental methods of the natural sciences.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] This means we must rest content with well-confirmed empirical generalisations, forever ignorant of "the ultimate original qualities of human nature".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] And in the absence of controlled experiments, we are left to "glean up our experiments in this science from a cautious observation of human life, and take them as they appear in the common course of the world, by men's behaviour in company, in affairs, and in their pleasures".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Hume begins by arguing that each simple idea is derived from a simple impression so that all our ideas are ultimately derived from experience: thus Hume accepts concept empiricism and rejects the purely intellectual and innate ideas found in rationalist philosophy.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Our complex ideas, he acknowledges, may not directly correspond to anything in experience (e.g., we can form the complex idea of a heavenly city).
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] But each *simple* idea (e.g., of the colour red) directly corresponds to a simple impression resembling it—and this regular correspondence suggests that the two are causally connected.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Since the simple impressions come before the simple ideas, and since those without functioning senses (e.g., blindness) end up lacking the corresponding ideas, Hume concludes that simple ideas must be derived from simple impressions.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Notoriously, Hume considers and dismisses the 'missing shade of blue' counterexample.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Briefly examining impressions, Hume then distinguishes between impressions of sensation (found in sense experience) and impressions of reflection (found mainly in emotional experience), only to set aside any further discussion for Book 2's treatment of the passions.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] But despite this freedom, the imagination still tends to follow general psychological principles as it moves from one idea to another: this is the "association of ideas".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Here Hume finds three "natural relations" guiding the imagination: resemblance, contiguity, and causation.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] But the imagination remains free to compare ideas along any of seven "philosophical relations": resemblance, identity, space/time, quantity/number, quality/degree, contrariety, and causation.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Hume finishes Part 1 by arguing (following Berkeley) that so-called "abstract ideas" are in fact only particular ideas used in a general way.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Thus the general term "triangle" both calls up an idea of some particular triangle and activates the custom disposing the imagination to call up any other ideas of particular triangles.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Finally, Hume uses this account to explain so-called "distinctions of reason" (e.g., distinguishing the motion of a body from the body itself).
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Though such distinctions are strictly impossible, Hume argues, we achieve the same effect by noting the various points of resemblance between different objects.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Hume's "system concerning space and time" features two main doctrines: the *finitist* doctrine that space and time are not infinitely divisible, and the *relationist* doctrine that space and time cannot be conceived apart from objects.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Hume begins by arguing that, since "the capacity of the mind is limited", our imagination and senses must eventually reach a minimum: ideas and impressions so minute as to be indivisible.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] And since nothing can be more minute, our indivisible ideas are "adequate representations of the most minute parts of [spatial] extension".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Upon consideration of these "clear ideas", Hume presents a few arguments to demonstrate that space and time are not infinitely divisible, but are instead composed of indivisible points.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] On his account, the idea of space is abstracted from our sense experience (arrangements of coloured or tangible points), and the idea of time from the changing succession of our own perceptions.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] And this means that space and time cannot be conceived on their own, apart from objects arranged in space or changing across time.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Thus we have no idea of absolute space and time, so that vacuums and time without change are ruled out.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Hume then defends his two doctrines against objections.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] In defending his finitism against mathematical objections, he argues that the *definitions* of geometry support his account.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Next, Hume defends his relationist doctrine, critically examining the alleged idea of a vacuum.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] In the final section, Hume accounts for our ideas of existence and of external existence.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] First, he argues that there is no distinct impression from which to derive the idea of existence.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Instead, this idea is nothing more than the idea of any object, so that thinking of something and thinking of it as existent is the very same thing.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Next, he argues that we cannot conceive of anything beyond our own perceptions; thus our conception of the existence of external objects is at most a "relative idea".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Hume recalls the seven philosophical relations, and divides them into two classes: four which can give us "knowledge and certainty", and three which cannot.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] (This division reappears in Hume's first *Enquiry* as "relations of ideas" and "matters of fact", respectively.) As for the four relations, he notes, all can yield knowledge by way of *intuition*: immediate recognition of a relation (e.g., one idea as brighter in colour than another).
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] But with one of the four, "proportions in quantity or number", we commonly achieve knowledge by way of *demonstration*: step-by-step inferential reasoning (e.g., proofs in geometry).
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Hume makes two remarks on demonstrative reasoning in mathematics: that geometry is not as precise as algebra (though still generally reliable), and that mathematical ideas are not "spiritual and refin'd perceptions", but instead copied from impressions.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] As for the other three relations, two of them (identity and space/time) are simply a matter of immediate sensory *perception* (e.g., one object next to another).
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] But with the last relation, causation, we can go beyond the senses, by way of a form of inferential reasoning he calls *probable reasoning*.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Here Hume embarks on his celebrated examination of causation, beginning with the question *From what impression do we derive our idea of causation?* All that can be observed in a single instance of cause and effect are two relations: contiguity in space, and priority in time.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] But Hume insists that our idea of causation also includes a mysterious *necessary connection* linking cause to effect.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] He concludes that our acceptance of this maxim must be somehow drawn "from observation and experience", and thus turns to the second question.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Hume develops a detailed three-stage psychological account of how probable reasoning works (i.e., how "the judgement" operates).
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] First, our senses or memory must present us with some object: our confidence in this perception (our "assent") is simply a matter of its force and vivacity.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Second, we must make an inference, moving from our perception of this object to an idea of another object: since the two objects are perfectly distinct from each other, this inference must draw on past experience of the two objects being observed together again and again.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] (This "constant conjunction" is promptly filed alongside contiguity and priority, in Hume's still-developing account of our idea of causation.) But what exactly is the process by which we draw on past experience and make an inference from the present object to the other object?
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Here the famous "problem of induction" arises.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Hume argues that this all-important inference cannot be accounted for by any process of reasoning: neither demonstrative reasoning nor probable reasoning.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Not demonstrative reasoning: it cannot be demonstrated that the future will resemble the past, for "[w]e can at least conceive a change in the course of nature", in which the future significantly differs from the past.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] And not probable reasoning: that kind of reasoning itself draws on past experience, which means it *presupposes* that the future will resemble the past.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] In other words, in explaining how we draw on past experience to make causal inferences, we cannot appeal to a kind of reasoning that itself draws on past experience—that would be a vicious circle that gets us nowhere.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] The inference is not based on reasoning, Hume concludes, but on the *association of ideas*: our innate psychological tendency to move along the three "natural relations".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Recall that one of the three is causation: thus when two objects are constantly conjoined in our experience, observing the one naturally leads us to form an idea of the other.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] This brings us to the third and final stage of Hume's account, our *belief* in the other object as we conclude the process of probable reasoning (e.g., seeing wolf tracks and concluding confidently that they were caused by wolves).
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] On his account of belief, the only difference between a *believed* idea and a merely *conceived* idea lies in the belief's additional force and vivacity.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] And there is a general psychological tendency for any lively perception to transfer some of its force and vivacity to any other perception naturally related to it (e.g., seeing "the picture of an absent friend" makes our idea of the friend more lively, by the natural relation of resemblance).
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Thus in probable reasoning, on Hume's account, our lively perception of the one object not only leads us to form a mere idea of the other object, but *enlivens* that idea into a full-fledged belief.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Hume now pauses for a more general examination of the psychology of belief.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Similarly, other kinds of custom-based conditioning (e.g., rote learning, repeated lying) can induce strong beliefs.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Next, Hume considers the mutual influence of reasoning and the passions, and of belief and the imagination.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Only beliefs can have motivational influence: it is the additional force and vivacity of a belief (as opposed to a mere idea) that makes it "able to operate on the will and passions".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] And in turn we tend to favor beliefs that flatter our passions.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Likewise, a story must be somewhat realistic or familiar to please the imagination, and an overactive imagination can result in delusional belief.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Hume sees these diverse phenomena as confirming his "force and vivacity" account of belief.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Indeed, we keep ourselves "from augmenting our belief upon every increase of the force and vivacity of our ideas" only by soberly reflecting on past experience and forming "general rules" for ourselves.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Hume then examines probable reasoning under conditions of empirical uncertainty, distinguishing "proofs" (conclusive empirical evidence) from mere "probabilities" (less than conclusive empirical evidence).
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Hume's discussion of probability finishes with a section on common cognitive biases, starting with recency effects.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] First, the more recent the event whose cause or effect we are looking for, the stronger our belief in the conclusion.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Second, the more recent the observations we draw on, the stronger our belief in the conclusion.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Third, the longer and more discontinuous a line of reasoning, the weaker our belief in the conclusion.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Fourth, irrational prejudices can be formed by overgeneralizing from experience: the imagination is unduly influenced by any "superfluous circumstances" that have frequently been observed to accompany the circumstances that actually matter.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] And paradoxically, the only way to correct for the pernicious influence of "general rules" is to follow other general rules, formed by reflecting on the circumstances of the case and our cognitive limitations.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Throughout the section, Hume uses his "force and vivacity" account of belief to account for these "unphilosophical" influences on our reasoning.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Having completed his account of probable reasoning, Hume returns to the mysterious idea of necessary connection.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] He rejects some proposed sources of this idea: not from the "known qualities of matter", nor from God, nor from some "unknown quality" of matter, nor from our power to move our body at will.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] For all ideas derive from experience, and in no single case do we observe anything like a necessary connection linking cause to effect.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] But the idea *does* arise upon repeated observations, and since mere repetition cannot produce anything new in the objects themselves, the idea must therefore derive from something new in our mind.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Thus he concludes that the idea of necessary connection is derived from inside: from the feeling we experience when the mind (conditioned by repeated observation) makes a causal inference.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] And though his conclusion is shocking to common sense, Hume explains it away by noting that "the mind has a great propensity to spread itself on external objects".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Finally, he offers two definitions of "cause": one in terms of the *objects* (viz. their relations of priority, contiguity, and constant conjunction), and another in terms of the *mind* (viz. the causal inference it makes upon observing the objects).
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Hume finishes Part 3 with two brief sections.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] First, he presents eight rules for empirically identifying true causes: after all, if we leave aside experience, "[a]ny thing may produce any thing".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Second, he compares human reason with animal reason, a comparison which clinches the case for his associationist account of probable reasoning: after all, animals are clearly capable of learning from experience through conditioning, and yet they are clearly incapable of any sophisticated reasoning.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Hume begins Part 4 by arguing that "all knowledge degenerates into probability", due to the possibility of error: even the rock solid certainty of mathematics becomes less than certain when we remember that we might have made a mistake somewhere.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] But things get worse: reflection on the fallibility of our mind, and meta-reflection on the fallibility of this first reflection, and so on *ad infinitum*, ultimately reduces probability into total scepticism—or at least it *would*, if our beliefs were governed by the understanding alone.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] But according to Hume, this "extinction of belief" does not actually happen: having beliefs is part of human nature, which only confirms Hume's account of belief as "more properly an act of the sensitive, than of the cogitative part of our natures".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] And as for *why* we do not sink into total scepticism, Hume argues that the mind has a limited quantity of "force and activity", and that difficult and abstruse reasoning "strain[s] the imagination", "hinder[ing] the regular flowing of the passions and sentiments".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] As a result, extremely subtle sceptical argumentation is unable to overpower and destroy our beliefs.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Next comes an extremely lengthy account of why we believe in an external physical world: i.e., why we think objects have a *continued* (existing when unobserved) and *distinct* (existing external to and independent of the mind) existence.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Hume considers three potential sources of this belief—the senses, reason, and the imagination.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] It's not the senses: clearly they are incapable of informing us of anything existing unobserved.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] And it's not reason: even children and fools believe in an external world, and nearly all of us naïvely take our perceptions to be objects with a continued and distinct existence, which goes *against* reason.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] So this belief must come from the imagination.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] But only some of our impressions bring about the belief: namely, impressions with *constancy* (invariableness in appearance over time) and *coherence* (regularity in changing appearances).
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Thus Hume proceeds to develop an account of how the imagination, fed with coherent and constant impressions, brings about belief in objects with continued (and therefore distinct) existence.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Given *coherent* impressions, we have only one way of accounting for our observations consistently with past experience: we form the supposition that certain objects exist unperceived.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] And since this supposes more regularity than is found in past observation, causal reasoning alone cannot explain it: thus Hume invokes the imagination's tendency to continue in any "train of thinking" inertially, "like a galley put in motion by the oars".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] But to explain "so vast an edifice, as... the continu'd existence of all external bodies", Hume finds it necessary to bring *constancy* into his account, as follows: (1) Identity is characterised as invariableness and uninterruptedness over time.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] (2) Since the mind tends to confuse closely resembling ideas, it will naturally confuse a case of interrupted observation of an invariable object with a case of perfect identity.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] (3) This combination of perfect identity and interrupted observation creates cognitive dissonance, which is resolved by fabricating continued existence.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] (4) This fiction is enlivened into a full-fledged belief by the memory's "lively impressions" of the observed object.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] But this naïve belief in the continued and distinct existence of our perceptions is *false*, as is easily shown by simple observations.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Philosophers therefore distinguish mental perceptions from external objects.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] But, Hume argues, this philosophical "system of a double existence" could never arise directly from reason or the imagination.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Instead, it is "the monstrous offspring of two principles", viz. our naïve belief in the continued and distinct existence of our perceptions, along with our more reflective conclusion that perceptions must depend upon the mind.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] It is only by passing through the naïve natural belief that the imagination fabricates this "arbitrarily invent[ed]" philosophical system.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Hume ends by voicing strong doubts about any system based on "such trivial qualities of the fancy", and recommending "[c]arelessness and in-attention" as the only remedy for scepticism.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Next, Hume presents a brief critique of "antient philosophy" (traditional Aristotelianism) and "modern philosophy" (post-Scientific Revolution mechanical philosophy), focusing on their rival conceptions of external objects.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] As for the incomprehensible "fictions of the antient philosophy", he thinks they can shed further light on human psychology.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] We begin with contradictions in "our ideas of bodies": between seeing bodies as ever-changing bundles of distinct qualities, and seeing bodies as simple unities that retain their identity across time.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] We reconcile these contradictions by fabricating "something unknown and invisible" that underlies change and unifies the distinct qualities together: i.e., the *substance* of traditional metaphysics.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Similar fictions, fabricated by the imagination to resolve similar difficulties, include *substantial forms*, *accidents*, and *occult qualities*, all meaningless jargon used only to hide our ignorance.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Modern philosophy, however, claims to disown the "trivial propensit[ies] of the imagination" and follow only solid reason (or, for Hume, "the solid, permanent, and consistent principles of the imagination").
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Its "fundamental principle" is that secondary qualities ("colours, sounds, tastes, smells, heat and cold") are "nothing but impressions in the mind", as opposed to the primary qualities ("motion, extension, and solidity") that exist in reality.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] But Hume argues that primary qualities cannot be conceived apart from the secondary qualities.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Thus if we follow solid reason and exclude the latter, we will be forced to contradict our own senses by excluding the former as well, thereby denying the entire external world.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Hume then examines "the nature of the mind", starting with the materialist-dualist debate over the substance of the mind.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] He rejects the whole question as "unintelligible", for we have no impression (and therefore no idea) of any substance, and defining "substance" as "something which may exist by itself" does not help (each of our perceptions, Hume argues, would then count as a distinct substance).
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Turning to the question of the "*local conjunction*" of mind and matter, he considers and endorses the anti-materialist argument which asks how unextended thoughts and feelings could possibly be conjoined at some location to an extended substance like a body.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] But the contrary problem arises for dualists: how can extended perceptions (of extended objects) possibly be conjoined to a simple substance?
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Finally, Hume weighs in on the topic of personal identity.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Notoriously, he claims that introspective experience reveals nothing like a *self* (i.e., a mental substance with identity and simplicity), but only an ever-changing bundle of particular perceptions.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] And so he gives a psychological account of why we believe in personal identity, arguing that "the identity, which we ascribe to the mind of man, is only a fictitious one, and of a like kind with that which we ascribe to vegetables and animal bodies".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] And consequently, leaving aside the fictions we invent, questions of personal identity are far too hazy to be answered with precision.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Hume finishes Book 1 with a deeply sceptical interlude.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Before continuing his "accurate anatomy of human nature" in Books 2 and 3, he anxiously ruminates: the "danger" of trusting his feeble faculties, along with the "solitude" of leaving behind established opinion, make his "bold enterprises" look foolhardy.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] And how much should we trust our imagination?
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Here a dilemma looms: if we follow the imagination wherever it leads, we end up with ridiculous absurdities; if we follow only its "general and more establish'd properties", we sink into total scepticism.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] As Hume writes: "[w]e have, therefore, no choice left but betwixt a false reason and none at all." Faced with this dilemma, we tend to just forget about it and move on, though Hume finds himself verging on an intellectual breakdown.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Hume begins by recalling Book 1's distinction between impressions of sensation ("original impressions", arising from physical causes outside the mind) and impressions of reflection ("secondary impressions", arising from other perceptions within the mind), examining only the latter.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Pride and humility are indirect passions, and Hume's account of the two is his leading presentation of the psychological mechanisms responsible for the indirect passions.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Since we cannot put the *feeling* of a passion into words, Hume identifies passions via their characteristic *causes and effects*.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] The *cause* of a passion is what calls up the passion: e.g., pride can be caused by one's beautiful house.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] A cause can be subdivided into the *subject* itself (e.g., one's house) and the *quality* of the subject that "operates on the passions" (e.g., the beauty of one's house).
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] The *object* of a passion is what the passion is ultimately directed at: pride and humility are both directed at oneself.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Hume's account relies on three mechanisms.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] First, the "association of ideas": the mind tends to move from one idea to another idea that is naturally related to it.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Second, the "association of impressions": the mind tends to move from one passion to another passion that resembles it in feeling (e.g., from joy to love).
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Third, their "mutual assistance": if we feel a passion towards something, we will tend to feel a resembling passion towards something else naturally related to it (e.g., from anger at one person to impatience at a related person).
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Applying all this to pride, Hume argues that the pleasant sensation of pride, directed at ourselves, naturally tends to be called up when something naturally related to ourselves produces a pleasant sensation of its own.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Likewise with humility: when something naturally related to ourselves produces an unpleasant sensation of its own, it tends to make us ashamed of ourselves.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] These indirect passions are thus the product of the "double relation of impressions and ideas".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Hume completes his account with five "limitations".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] First, in order for pride or humility to be produced, the relation of ideas must be a relatively close one.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Second, because our judgements are strongly influenced by "comparison", this relation must apply only to ourselves or a few others.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Third, the cause of pride or humility must be something evident to ourselves and others.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Fourth, this cause must be a long-lasting one.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Fifth, general rules have a strong influence on our passions, leading us to overlook occasional anomalies.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] In the next three sections, Hume puts his account to the test by examining three causes of pride and humility: the qualities of one's mind, of one's body, and of external objects.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] First, the qualities of the mind: our virtues and vices.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Here Hume's main point is that, whatever the true nature of moral evaluation, whether it is a matter of innate moral psychology (Hume's own view), or instead self-interest and cultural training (the view of Hobbes and Mandeville), his account will hold up.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] For, on either theory, virtues produce a pleasant sensation of their own and vices a painful sensation of their own.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Next come the qualities of the body: physical beauty and deformity.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Here Hume's main point is that the beauty or deformity of something's structure is nothing more than its power to produce pleasure or pain in us.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Finally, Hume examines the qualities of external objects related to us.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Though the natural relation of *resemblance* has little influence, he explains, external objects do not cause pride or humility without some relation of *contiguity* or *causation*—a fact he takes to confirm his overall account.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] After a few minor illustrations, Hume explains why pride in one's ancestors is magnified when the family enjoys uninterrupted possession of land, and when it is passed down from male to male (both of the conditions, he claims, serve to strengthen the relation of ideas).
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Hume devotes an entire section to "property and riches".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] But it is more difficult to accommodate *riches*: i.e., the mere power of acquiring the comforts of life.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] For Hume's earlier account of causation eliminated the distinction between power and the exercise of power, as well as the very idea of an unexercised power—and how can I take pride in mere coins and paper without such an idea?
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Hume finishes by noting the pride we take in power over others, a pride enhanced by comparing our condition to theirs (thus humans are prouder to own other humans than to own sophisticated machinery).
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Hume's next section adds a new kind of cause of pride and humility: viz., *reputation*, a "secondary cause" grounded in the enormously important mechanism of *sympathy*.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] For Hume, sympathy with others, or "communication", is that mechanism by which we naturally tend to receive and share in the passions and opinions of those we feel close to.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] We start by observing "external signs" (e.g., smiling or speaking) and forming an idea of another's sentiments.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Since our extremely vivid conception of ourselves will tend to enliven any related idea, the closer the relation we see between ourselves and the other person, the more vivid our idea of their sentiments.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] And if this relation is close enough, we will end up actually feeling their passion or believing their opinion: i.e., our idea of their passion or opinion will grow so lively as to become the very passion or opinion itself.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] This mirrors Hume's earlier account of causal reasoning: both processes move along the three natural relations, channeling the force and vivacity of vivid perceptions into faint ideas, enlivening them into much stronger perceptions.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Pride or shame in one's reputation, Hume continues, stems primarily from the sympathetically communicated opinions of others.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] But additional factors play a role: others might be seen as a good judge of character ("authority"), and the very question of one's self-worth is both emotionally heightened and apt to evoke a self-conscious deference to the opinions of others.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] The resulting account explains various observations: why pride is affected more by the opinions of certain people (those whose character we like, whose judgement we respect, or who we have known for a long time), and less by opinions we know to be false (and thus cannot share in).
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Hume finishes by illustrating and confirming his account with a concrete example (viz., a man from a high-class family fallen on hard times leaving home to do manual labour elsewhere), and considering some minor objections.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] In the final section, Hume seeks to confirm his overall account of pride and humility by applying it to animals.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Hume's treatment of love and hatred is much like his treatment of pride and humility: all four are indirect passions produced by a double relation of impressions and ideas.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] As Part 2 begins, he again distinguishes object from cause, and quality from subject; whereas pride and humility were directed at oneself, love and hatred is directed at "some other person".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] As before, a relation of ideas is needed between the cause of love or hatred and the person loved or hated, and a relation of impressions between the cause (with a pleasant or unpleasant sensation of its own) and the resulting love or hatred.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] And since pride and love are closely connected (as Hume observes, we seek to win others' love by showcasing the qualities we take pride in), the arguments of Part 1 can simply be carried over.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] In a series of eight "experiments", Hume tests his account against observations drawn from ordinary life.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] The final four experiments focus on how easily a transition is made from one passion to another.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] As Hume's account would predict, we easily go from love and hatred to pride and humility: e.g., I can take pride in my relation to someone else with lovable qualities.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Curiously, however, the reverse does not hold: e.g., my pride in my own qualities will not lead me to love someone else for their relation to me.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] To explain this, Hume argues that the imagination has trouble going from lively ideas to obscure ideas (e.g., from the idea of oneself to that of another person).
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Next, as Hume's account would also predict, we easily transition from love of one person to love of others related to this person.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] But the transition is easiest when we "descend" from the greater to the lesser: e.g., "'tis more natural for us to love the son upon account of the father, than the father upon account of the son".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] And yet the imagination has the opposite tendency: e.g., moving easily from Jupiter's moons to Jupiter itself.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] To resolve this difficulty, Hume argues that it is easier for the passions to make minor changes (adding in the love of a related *lesser* person) than major changes (adding in the love of a related *greater* person), and that the passions "are a more powerful principle than the imagination".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Finally, Hume acknowledges a case where we can move easily from pride to love: "when the very cause of the pride and humility is plac'd in some other person", e.g. when your praise of me excites my pride and I end up loving you for it.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] But this exception only confirms Hume's account: since the first passion arises from the other person, we easily move to a passion directed at that same person.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Hume then confronts an objection: his account ignores intention, having us love or hate those who bring us pleasure or pain even where this is completely unintended.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] In response, Hume insists that qualities unrelated to intentional action really can elicit love or hatred, so long as the qualities are "constant and inherent in [someone's] person and character": e.g., disliking someone for their ugliness or stupidity.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] It is with isolated actions that intention is important: it "connect[s the action] with the person" and can also amplify the pleasantness or unpleasantness of the action, whereas "entirely involuntary and accidental" actions arouse only mild or short-lived passions.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] In a further illustration, Hume considers our emotional reaction to those who harm us from perfectly justified motives (e.g., judges, competitors): though we will not hate them if we are reasonable, we often hate them anyway, even inventing reasons to hate them.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] In the next two sections, Hume uses sympathy to account for some particular causes of love and hatred.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] First, "*relation*, *acquaintance*, and *resemblance*": we sometimes love others not for their personal qualities, but simply because they are related to us, familiar to us, or similar to us.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] In these cases, pleasure arises from the sheer stimulating effects of sympathy: family members, neighbors, and acquaintances are a durable source of lively ideas, as are individuals with personal qualities resembling our own.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] And as Hume puts it, "[e]very lively idea is agreeable, but especially that of a passion".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Second, we sometimes esteem people not for their personal qualities, but simply for being rich and powerful (esteem and contempt being "species of love and hatred").
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] To account for this phenomenon, Hume identifies three candidate "principles": (1) We enjoy thinking of their luxuries.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] (2) We think they might give us some of their wealth.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] He then argues that the third principle, sympathy, is by far the most important.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] The first principle has some influence on its own, but mostly operates by means of sympathy.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] And the second principle has little influence: it is relatively rare to receive any personal advantage from the rich and powerful, and we esteem them even when this is known to be impossible.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Hume closes the section with an overview of "the force of sympathy".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Many animals, and especially humans, have a psychological need for social interaction.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Moreover, sympathy with usefulness explains "[m]ost kinds of beauty": e.g., the convenience of a house, the fertility of a field.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Lastly, Hume observes that "the minds of men are mirrors to one another": a rich man enjoys his luxuries, which brings esteem from others, which in turn excites the rich man's pride, which encourages further pursuit of riches.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] The next six sections are dedicated to an examination of the "compound passions", i.e. passions arising from "the mixture of love and hatred with other emotions".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Hume begins with *benevolence* and *anger*, motivational "desires" aimed at bringing about "the happiness or misery of the person belov'd or hated".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] This marks an important contrast: love and hatred have innate motivational consequences, whereas pride and humility are only "pure emotions in the soul".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Like benevolence and anger, they are motivational desires aimed at bringing about another's happiness or misery; but unlike benevolence and anger, they apply quite generally—not only to those we love or hate, but even to complete strangers.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Thus Hume calls them "counterfeited" versions of benevolence and anger.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Pity (also called "compassion") is received by sympathetic communication: anyone can arouse our pity, just by communicating "their interests, their passions, their pains and pleasures" to us.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Even people who show no emotion at their misfortune can arouse our pity due to the influence of general rules on our imagination.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Hume also uses comparison to account for *envy*: the unpleasant feeling we experience when another's "present enjoyment" makes our own happiness seem diminished by comparison.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] The following section sees Hume amending his account in response to a problem.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] If love and hatred are produced by anyone who brings us pleasure or pain, as Hume has argued, then we should love those who bring us malicious joy, and hate those who bring us the pain of pity.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] But this runs contrary to experience: we tend to hate the objects of our malice, and love the objects of our pity.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Hume resolves this problem by introducing a new kind of relation of impressions: in addition to "the resemblance of sensations", there is also "the parallel direction of the desires".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Thus the connection between pity and love, and between malice and hatred, lies in their motivational tendencies (which run parallel to each other), not in the way they feel (which run contrary to each other).
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Hume gives examples to illustrate and confirm this "principle of a parallel direction", including a discussion of the emotions found in business rivals and business partners.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] But another problem arises: since Hume says we have esteem for the rich and contempt for the poor, how can he say we tend to love the objects of our pity?
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Hume's solution presents us with three levels of sympathy with misfortune: (1) weak sympathy, which makes us feel only the present misfortune of the afflicted, producing only contemptuous pity; (2) strong sympathy (i.e.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] And because we have "a much stronger propensity to pride than to humility", there is more pride in contempt than there is humility in respect.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Hume then acknowledges a problem: why, given his account, are love and hatred not *always* accompanied by respect and contempt?
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Hume finishes with an explanation of why social inferiors are expected to keep their distance from their superiors.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] The final compound passion is "the amorous passion", i.e. romantic love.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] It consists of three distinct passions: a sense of beauty, libido, and kindness.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] These three passions are bound together both by "resemblance" (all have a pleasant sensation) and by "a parallel desire" (all have related motivational tendencies).
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Accordingly, any one of them can end up producing the other two, with beauty most likely to produce the other two (kindness and libido being "too remote" from each other, and beauty "plac'd in a just medium betwixt them").
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Hume argues that this phenomenon reinforces his "double relation of impressions and ideas" account.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Hume finishes Part 2 with his last section on animal psychology.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Love and hatred, he writes, can be produced in animals simply by the pain or pleasure felt from an object, or by such relations as "acquaintance" and "likeness" of species.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Sympathy works to spread feelings (e.g. fear, grief) from one animal to another, keep animal play from leading to injury, and animate a pack of hunting dogs beyond their individual level of excitement.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] In general, Hume remarks, the psychological mechanisms at work do not require any sophisticated "force of reflection or penetration": "[e]very thing is conducted by springs and principles, which are not peculiar to man, or any one species of animals".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] In Part 3, Hume begins examining the motives that bring us to action.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] After a glancing mention of the direct passions and a perfunctory definition of the will as a mere impression we feel, he confronts the hoary philosophical problem of free will and determinism, dedicating two sections to a defense of soft determinist compatibilism.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] In the first section, he makes a case for "the doctrine of necessity".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] The issue, as Hume sees it, is whether human action is determined by a necessity comparable to "*physical necessity*"—the necessity that governs physical objects.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Thus, given Hume's idiosyncratic account of necessity, it is hard to deny that human action is governed by necessity.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] In the next section, Hume challenges "the doctrine of liberty"—the view that human beings are endowed with a distinctive kind of indeterministic free will—by setting out and debunking "the reasons for [its] prevalence".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] First, since we confuse necessity with violent constraint, we end up confusing freedom from necessity (the indeterministic "liberty of *indifference*") with freedom from violent constraint (the compatibilist "liberty of *spontaneity*").
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Second, we are deceived by a "false sensation of liberty": when deliberating about our own actions, there is "a certain looseness" to the will, so that we can easily produce an "image or faint motion" for each alternative course of action.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Thus, we end up convinced that we really could have acted differently, even though "a spectator can commonly infer our actions from our motives and character".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Finally, we mistakenly think necessity poses a threat to moral responsibility, and is therefore "dangerous... to religion and morality".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] After noting that being *dangerous* is not the same as being *false*, Hume recalls that his "necessity" is a very attenuated one: there is nothing dangerous or even controversial about saying that constant conjunction and causal inference apply to human action as well as physical objects.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Thus, the threat to moral responsibility comes not from *necessity*, but from *indeterministic liberty*.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Hume then passes from the will itself to the motivational factors that determine voluntary actions.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Against the traditional view that reason and the passions frequently come into motivational conflict, Hume argues that reason is incapable of opposing the passions, and that the passions cannot run contrary to reason.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] First, reason alone cannot motivate us—it can only perform demonstrative or causal reasoning.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] And since abstract demonstrations influence us only by directing causal reasoning (e.g., doing math to pay your debts), and causal reasoning influences us only by directing preexisting motives (e.g., figuring out how to make the food you want), reason itself cannot bring about any motivation.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] And this in turn means it cannot counteract or regulate the passions: on the contrary, "[r]eason is, and ought only to be the slave of the passions".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Second, passions cannot be in agreement or disagreement with reason: for this is a matter of the agreement or disagreement between an idea and the object it represents, and passions do not represent anything else.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Thus Hume notoriously writes: "'Tis not contrary to reason to prefer the destruction of the whole world to the scratching of my finger".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Of course, if a passion is based on a false judgement—about an object that does not really exist, or a causal relation that does not really hold—then the passion can be considered "unreasonable" in a less strict sense of the term.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] But "even then", insists Hume, "'tis not the passion, properly speaking, which is unreasonable, but the judgment".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Finally, Hume argues that the alleged conflict between reason and the passions is actually a conflict between two different kinds of passions—the calm passions and the violent passions.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Since both the calm passions and reason "operat[e] with the same calmness and tranquility", we confuse them with each other and mistakenly suppose our calm passions to be "determinations of reason".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] The following five sections examine the factors which give passions their motivational force.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Unsurprisingly, the violence of a passion makes it stronger; but even a calm passion can be extremely strong due to "repeated custom and its own force", especially when it has been "corroborated by reflection, and seconded by resolution".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Nevertheless, since "[g]enerally speaking, the violent passions have a more powerful influence on the will", Hume focuses on the factors which increase the violence of passions.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] First, when a "predominant passion" is accompanied by other "inferior" passions, it can acquire violence by "swallow[ing them] up": e.g., strong love can be made more violently passionate by a touch of anger.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Other psychological phenomena (e.g., opposition, uncertainty, obscurity) can produce the same effect by stimulating us with agitation and mental effort.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Next, "custom and repetition" can both leave us with a direct inclination to perform the activity we are repeating and also affect the violence of related passions.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Hume discusses three stages of repeated activity: (1) The sheer novelty of unfamiliar activities makes our feelings more intense, either magnifying our pain or adding on the pleasure of "wonder [and] surprise".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] (2) An activity performed with "moderate facility" is "an infallible source of pleasure" (cf.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] "flow"), sometimes even converting pain into enjoyment.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] (3) But excessive repetition can make formerly pleasant activities so dull as to be unpleasant.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Our passions can also acquire violence from *the vivacity of our ideas*.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Thus particular ideas make for more violent passions than general ideas, and so too for fresh memories, conventional ideas, and ideas enlivened by great eloquence or passionate delivery.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] And, as in Book 1, only beliefs (as opposed to "mere[s] fiction of the imagination") can call up any of our passions.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Hume also devotes two sections to examining the vivacity of our ideas of *space and time* and the corresponding effect on our passions.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] (2) Distance in time is associated with a greater reduction than distance in space, because our sensory experience makes it easier to hold an array of spatial points in mind than an array of temporal points.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] (3) The distant past is associated with a greater reduction than the distant future, because it is easier for the mind to go with the flow of time than to go against it.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] (2) Distance in time has a greater effect than distance in space (e.g., ancient relics are more admired than furniture from abroad), because we are challenged and invigorated by the greater difficulty of mentally traversing distance in time.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] (3) The distant past has a greater effect than the distant future (e.g., we admire our ancestors more than our posterity), because we are challenged and invigorated by the greater difficulty of going against the flow of time.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Hume finishes with a convenient summary of the preceding six sections.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] At last Hume examines *the direct passions*, dividing them into two classes.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] First and most prominently, there are those direct passions which arise immediately from pleasure or pain (in Hume's terminology, "good or evil")—this is simply due to "an *original* instinct" that orients us towards pleasure and away from pain.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] *Joy* and *grief*/*sorrow* arise from pleasure or pain that is "certain or probable".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] *Hope* and *fear* arise from pleasure or pain that is "uncertain" to some degree.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] *Desire*and*aversion* arise from pleasure and pain "consider'd simply".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] And *the will* "exerts itself" when pleasure or the absence of pain is within our power to obtain.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Second, there are those direct passions which "arise from a natural impulse or instinct, which is perfectly unaccountable": here Hume mentions benevolence, anger, hunger, and lust (in section 3 he had mentioned self-preservation and the love of one's children).
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] These diverse instinct-based passions, Hume writes, "produce good and evil [i.e., pleasure and pain]", as opposed to the other direct passions, which arise from pleasure and pain.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Hume spends the rest of the section on *hope and fear*, starting with a simple account based on probability.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] In conditions of uncertainty, as the imagination fluctuates between a pleasant scenario and an unpleasant scenario, the passions follow suit, fluctuating between joy and grief.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] And since different passions can blend together (like the lingering notes of a string instrument), the mixture of joy and grief will end up producing either hope or fear.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Even utterly irrelevant circumstances, or something expected to be *pleasant*, can call up fear if shrouded in uncertainty.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Hume closes the section by begging off any discussion of subtle "variations" of hope and fear, or of the role of the will and the direct passions in animals.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Book 2 finishes with a brief section on *curiosity*—"the love of truth", which leads us to take pleasure in intellectual pursuits and achievements.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] For both the abstract truths of "mathematics and algebra" and the real-world truths of "morals, politics, natural philosophy", we do not care much about truth "merely as such".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Instead, there are three other factors chiefly responsible for "the pleasure of study": (1) Intellectual challenge: the exercise must force us to "fix our attention and exert our genius".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] (2) Importance/utility: the topic must be useful or important enough to "fix our attention" via "a remote sympathy" with those our work might help (a sympathy that even motivates scholars lacking in "public spirit").
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] (3) Direct concern: just as hunters and gamblers begin to care about success itself more than the reward it brings, likewise scholars begin to develop a direct concern for the scholarly problems they work on (this due to the aforementioned principle of a "parallel direction").
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Finally, Hume offers an account of the *social curiosity* that fuels gossip: since doubt and uncertainty are painful, especially when they concern events whose ideas are forceful, we are naturally curious about the happenings of our immediate social environment.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Hume begins Book 3 by examining the nature of moral evaluation, offering a critique of moral rationalism and a defense of moral sentimentalism: in the terms of his overall system, Hume is arguing that the evaluations in our mind are *impressions*, not *ideas*.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] His main target is the rationalism of such philosophers as Clarke and Balguy, which posits "eternal fitnesses and unfitnesses of things, which are the same to every rational being that considers them", in effect classifying morality alongside mathematics under "relations of ideas".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Hume's principal arguments against this rationalism rest on Book 2's thesis that there is no opposition between reason and the passions: reason alone cannot motivate us, and "passions, volitions, and actions" cannot be in agreement or disagreement with reason.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Nor can the morality of an action be founded on the true or false judgements causally linked to it: no immoral action is wrong due to its arising from a mistake of fact, or (contra Wollaston) due to its causing false judgements in others.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] After summing up this critique, Hume develops a "more particular" case against rationalism, recalling his system's two kinds of reasoning: "the comparing of ideas" and "the inferring of matter of fact".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Consider the immorality of parricide and incest: this cannot consist merely in the abstract relations at play, for the very same relations can be found in perfectly non-moral contexts involving inanimate objects and animals.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] This first section ends with the famous is-ought paragraph.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Hume is thus left endorsing a moral sentimentalism somewhat like that of Hutcheson: "Morality... is more properly felt than judg'd of".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] The moral evaluations in our mind are impressions—"nothing but *particular* pains or pleasures"—and Hume's task is to explain how certain kinds of "action, or sentiment, or character" produce these special moral sentiments in us.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] But a problem arises: since pleasant or painful feelings can be produced by inanimate objects, why does sentimentalism not succumb to the same objection Hume has just raised against rationalism?
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Second, he reminds us that the four indirect passions are produced by pleasant or unpleasant qualities in *ourselves or other persons*, not inanimate objects.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] This objection dispatched, Hume closes with two points about the psychological origin of moral sentiments.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] First, on the working assumption that nature tends to produce variety from "a few principles", he hopes to find "general principles" underlying our moral psychology.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Before proceeding to his detailed examination of moral psychology, Hume takes a parting shot at moral rationalism and its "incomprehensible relations and qualities, which never did exist in nature, nor even in our imagination, by any clear and distinct conception".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Hume devotes Part 2 to the "artificial virtues": those positive character traits that would have no moral appeal were it not for social conventions established by human artifice.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] The most important of these virtues is *justice*, and in the first section Hume offers his so-called "circle argument" to show that justice would not be seen as a virtue in a hypothetical world lacking the relevant social conventions.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] First, Hume contends, *character-based motives* are morally more fundamental than *actions*: we approve of an action only insofar as it indicates some virtuous motive in the agent's character, so that what makes an action virtuous in the first place is the virtuous motive it proceeds from.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] But this motive must be an ordinary motive in human nature, as opposed to the distinctive moral motive of *performing the action because it is virtuous* (i.e., a "sense of duty").
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] After all, this moral motive presupposes that the action already counts as virtuous, and it would be circular to derive the action's virtue from a motive which itself presupposes the action's virtue.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] And so if justice were a natural virtue, there would have to be an ordinary motive in human nature that could make someone obey the rules of justice.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Thus there is no motive capable of making justice count as a virtue, not until certain social conventions come into place.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Hume closes this section by adding that we evaluate motives largely by comparison with what we consider to be normal human psychology, and that the rules of justice are so "obvious" and "necessary" an invention that they can still be deemed "natural" to the human species.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Hume next devotes an important and lengthy section to two questions: First, how is the social convention of justice established?
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] And second, why do we invest the rules of justice with moral significance?
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] His answer to the first question begins with our need for society.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Humans are not strong, skilled, or secure enough to meet our needs alone, and only society can offer additional labour force, specialisation, and mutual aid—all important advantages of society learned of through growing up in families.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] But this necessary social union is threatened both by human selfishness (or rather "confin'd generosity") and by the scarcity and instability of external goods.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] He insists that this convention is not a *promise*, famously illustrating the point with the example of two men agreeing to row a boat together, simply from a sense of mutual advantage rather than from any promise.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] And as justice is defined in terms of such a convention, so too the related concepts of "*property*, or *right*, or *obligation*" can mean nothing in its absence.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Since the chief obstacle to society (our selfishness, especially our insatiable acquisitiveness) is in fact the very motive responsible for society, the growth of social order depends less on our moral qualities than on our intellectual qualities.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] But since stabilizing external goods is such a "simple and obvious" rule, the convention is established with little delay, so that "the *state of nature*" is a "mere philosophical fiction"—not very realistic but useful for theorizing.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Real-world cases also illustrate the idea: close personal relationships bring one's private belongings into common ownership, and free goods like air and water are allowed unrestricted use.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] And this general point, Hume says, reinforces three earlier points: (1) Public benevolence cannot be why we obey the rules of justice, for it would only make these rules pointless.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] (2) Moral rationalism cannot make sense of justice: mere abstract reasoning can neither account for the fact that justice hinges on specific background conditions, nor produce the concern for our interests that originally leads us to establish the rules of justice.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] (3) Justice is an artificial virtue: though the whole purpose of justice is to serve our interests, the connection between justice and our interests dissolves in the absence of the relevant social convention.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] For without this convention, wholehearted pursuit of the *public interest* would make justice pointless and unrestrained pursuit of *private interests* would leave justice in ruins.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Hume's answer to the second question is that our approval of justice and disapproval of injustice is based in *sympathy with the public interest*.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Justice was established to serve our interests, but when society grows large enough, we might lose sight of how injustice threatens social order.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Fortunately, the threat can be made vivid again when I myself am the victim of injustice, or when I impartially sympathise with others threatened by injustice.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Their sympathetically communicated negative feelings form the basis of my disapproval of injustice, and this evaluation subsequently extends to my own behavior through the influence of general rules and sympathy with the opinions of others.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Three additional factors then reinforce these moral sentiments: (1) Public leaders propagandise on behalf of justice (contra Mandeville, this technique works only by appealing to and intensifying moral sentiments we already have).
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] (2) Parents instill children with a reliable and deeply rooted concern for the rules of justice.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] (3) Concern for reputation makes us scrupulously avoid injustice as a matter of personal principle.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] The next four sections see Hume completing his examination of justice as an artificial virtue: he argues that "the three fundamental laws of nature, *that of the stability of possession*, *of its transference by consent*, and *of the performance of promises*" are all based on human convention.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] He begins by discussing the general rule of *stability* and its applications.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] To make a peaceful establishment of society, we must avoid controversial "particular judgements" about who is best suited to make use of what resources, and instead adopt a general rule of *present possession*, simply as a "natural expedient" with all the appeal of custom.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Once society has been established, the additional rules of *occupation* (i.e.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] "first possession"), *prescription* (i.e.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] "the fruits of our garden"), and *succession* (i.e. inheritance) are developed.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] These rules are largely the product of the imagination, with ownership determined by the association of ideas.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Second, because "rigid stability" would of course bring great disadvantages (resources having been allocated by mere "chance"), we need a peaceful way to induce changes in ownership: thus we adopt the "obvious" rule of *transference by consent*.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Hume then examines the final "law of nature"—*the performance of promises*—giving a two-stage argument that promise-keeping is an artificial virtue.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] First, promises are naturally unintelligible, for there is no distinctive mental act for promises to express, neither *resolutions* nor *desires* nor a direct *willing* of the act.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] And as for *willing an obligation*, this is too absurd to be plausible: given that changes in obligation require changes in human sentiment, it is plainly impossible to will an obligation into existence.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] But second, even if promises *were* naturally intelligible, they could not create an obligation: i.e., even if we were foolish enough to mentally will an obligation, nothing would change, since no voluntary act could ever change human sentiments.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Hume also reprises the circle argument, arguing that there is no motive for promise-keeping other than a sense of duty in doing so.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] How, then, does the artificial convention of promising come about?
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] The first two laws of nature, for all their usefulness, leave many further opportunities for mutual advantage unrealised (e.g., non-simultaneous cooperative exchanges of labour), unable to overcome the meanness of human nature in the absence of "mutual confidence and security".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] The convention is then made moral in the same way as before ("*[p]ublic interest*, *education*, and *the artifices of politicians*") and a fictional act of the mind ("*willing* an obligation") is fabricated to make sense of the moral obligation.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Finally, Hume reviews these "laws of nature" and offers three additional arguments for their artificiality.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] (1) Justice is commonly defined in terms of property, and yet it is impossible to understand property except in terms of justice.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] But since there is no natural sentiment of approval for the practice of justice described in neutral language, "abstracting from the notio[n] of *property*" (e.g., restoring an object to its first possessor), justice is not a natural virtue.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] (2) Justice and injustice come in bright lines and sharp boundaries, whereas our natural moral sentiments come in degrees.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] In the next six sections, Hume completes his "system concerning the laws of nature and nations" with a lengthy discussion of *government*.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Hume then critiques the liberal Whig theory of government as deriving its authority only from the consent of the governed, as traced back to an original contract between ruler and people.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] But though government typically originates in a social agreement, promising cannot be its one and only source of authority.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] For, as Hume has argued, promise-keeping itself originates in a social convention serving the public interest, so that if government serves the public interest by "preserv[ing] order and concord in society", then it gains an authority of its own equivalent to that of promise-keeping.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] And the two run parallel *morally* as well: promise-breaking and anti-government action are both disapproved of primarily from a sense of common interest.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Thus there is no sense founding the one in the other.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] But Hume agrees with the Whigs about the right of resistance when governments become tyrannical.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Our *interest* in government consists in "the security and protection, which we enjoy in political society", and therefore disappears as soon as the authorities become intolerably oppressive.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] And though our *moral* obligation to allegiance might be expected to linger on stubbornly due to the influence of general rules, our familiarity with human nature and the history of tyrants will give us additional general rules marking out exceptions to the common rule.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] And thus public opinion ("perfectly infallible" in questions of morality) is not wed to any exceptionless rule of "passive obedience", but is perfectly willing to "make allowances for resistance in the more flagrant instances of tyranny and oppression".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] The next problem of allegiance is *who exactly is the rightful ruler?* And according to Hume, such questions are often irresolvable by reason, and it can be wise to simply go with the flow in the "interests of peace and liberty".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Again, Hume agrees that political society begins with a social agreement promising allegiance to certain people.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] But once a government acquires its own authority by serving the public interest, it is (paradoxically) in our interest to renounce our interest and simply abide the powers that be, lest we fall into divisive controversies over the best possible ruler.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] And with so many distinct principles, the choice of ruler is sometimes wonderfully clear, and sometimes hopelessly unclear.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Hume then examines international law: the similarities between individuals and entire nations yield the same three laws of nature as before, but the special needs of nations call for special rules (e.g., diplomatic immunity).
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Only general practice can determine exactly how much weaker the obligation is, and indeed the fact that the rules are recognised to be weaker in practice shows that people have "an implicit notion" of their artificiality.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] The final section examines the social rules governing the sexual behavior of women ("chastity and modesty"), which Hume takes to nicely illustrate how artificial virtues grounded only in social interest can nevertheless acquire universal force.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] It is boringly obvious that these rules are not exactly natural, and yet they solve a natural problem: a child needs both parents, parents need to know the child is theirs, and paternity is subject to uncertainty.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] And since questions of sexual fidelity cannot be settled in courtrooms, society needs informal norms (with weakened evidential standards and heightened reputational import) policing fidelity in women.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Indeed, Hume adds, given female weakness in the face of sexual temptation, society needs women to feel a strong aversion to anything even suggestive of infidelity.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Men instead stake their reputation on courage (a partly natural virtue) and enjoy looser sexual norms, fidelity in males (like cooperation among nations) being less important for society.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Hume finishes the *Treatise* by examining the "natural virtues": those character traits approved of independently of social conventions.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] In a general review of morality and the passions, he reminds us that human psychology is driven by pain and pleasure, which call up direct passions and then the indirect passions that explain moral evaluation and which "qualities or characters" count as virtuous or not.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] And since the indirect passions apply to actions only as indicating something stable in the agent's mind, the moral sentiments are also directed primarily at "mental qualities" and only derivatively at actions.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] After this review, Hume presents his central "hypothesis" concerning the natural virtues and vices: moral evaluation of these traits is best explained in terms of sympathy.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Given these three points, and given that natural virtues and social utility often go together, parsimony dictates that we also explain the natural virtues in terms of sympathy.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Hume finds the connection between virtue and utility fairly obvious: it inspired Mandeville's erroneous account of virtue as a fraudulent invention of conniving politicians, and indeed the connection is even stronger with natural virtues than with artificial virtues.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] For though artificial virtues may harm society in particular cases (promoting the public interest only when mediated by a "general scheme"), natural virtues help society in every case, which makes it even more probable that sympathy explains moral evaluation of the natural virtues.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Hume further develops his sympathy-based account of the natural virtues by considering two objections.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] First, *variability and impartiality*: how can something as variable as sympathy account for moral impartiality of the sort that recognises virtue in loved ones and complete strangers alike?
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Indeed, we perform similar corrections for our senses and our aesthetic judgements.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Of course, our passions may resist correction, so that only our language is changed; but we still know that our emotional favoritism of some over others would go away if we were equally close to them all, which is perhaps enough to settle "a general calm determination of the passions".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Second, *moral luck*: how can sympathy explain cases where unusual external circumstances have prevented someone's internal character from having its usual effects?
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Hume's answer is that the imagination follows general rules, focusing more on something's general tendencies than its actual effects, and that our moral sentiments are influenced accordingly.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Naturally, we will feel even stronger approval when the general tendency is actually realised, but we deliberately set aside moral luck to correct our general moral judgements.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] This explains how we can manage such "extensive sympathy" in morality despite our "limited generosity" in practice: it takes "*real consequences*" and particular cases to "touch the heart" and "controul our passions", but "*seeming tendencies*" and general trends are enough to "influence our taste".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] He finishes this general treatment of the natural virtues with a fourfold classification: every natural virtue is either (1) useful to others, (2) useful to the person himself, (3) immediately agreeable to others, or (4) immediately agreeable to the person himself.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] The two categories of useful virtues are often blended together by sympathy: what hurts me ends up paining others as they sympathise with me, and what hurts others ends up paining me as I sympathise with them.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Less important are the virtues of immediate agreeableness: instead of reflecting on the positive tendencies of a mental quality, we simply find it pleasant in and of itself (e.g. wit, insouciance).
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] And even here sympathy plays a major role: we approve of these virtues in large part because they bring pleasure to others or the person himself.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Hume then applies his "general system of morals" to two kinds of virtue: the rough "heroic virtue" of the *great*, and the kind-hearted virtue of the *good*.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] As for heroic virtue, it derives its merit from a suspect source: pride.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Pride has a bad name because the idea of someone superior to us can be so immediately disagreeable, but Hume distinguishes between "ill-grounded" and "well-grounded" pride.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Ill-grounded pride pains us by *comparison*, when someone else overrates their own merit and this idea of a superior becomes more than an "idle" fiction and reaches a medium level of strength.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] But someone else's well-grounded pride brings us pleasure by *sympathy*, when the idea is so strong in us that we fully believe in their merit.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] And thus well-grounded pride is a virtue, thanks to its usefulness and agreeableness to the person himself.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Now, because we are so prone to the vice of excessive pride, social harmony demands artificial rules ("*rules of good-breeding*") against the open expression of any pride at all.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] But "a man of honour" is still expected to have a healthy internal sense of his own merit, and those whose modesty goes too far are scorned for their "meanness" or "simplicity".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Thus it is that heroic virtues—"[c]ourage, intrepidity, ambition, love of glory, magnanimity, and all the other shining virtues of that kind"—are chiefly admired for the "well-regulated pride" they embody.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Hume adds that our disapproval of open pride even in those who have never insulted us (e.g. historical figures) is due to an additional sympathy with the people around them.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] As for the virtues of "goodness and benevolence", Hume explains their merit primarily in terms of their positive impact on others.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] The section begins by reviewing Hume's account of moral evaluation from the common point of view, and of sympathy with a person's sphere of influence.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Here the "tender passions" are not only themselves good for society, they are needed to direct other virtues towards the public good.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] But there is also a more immediate approval, as we are simply "touch'd with a tender sentiment" or sympathetic to characters like our own—this is why even benevolent "trifles" and excesses in love still win approval, as the love in their minds easily converts into love in our minds for them.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Indeed, in general, your moral virtue is mostly determined by how desirable you are in different social relations.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Hume finishes by explaining how his system accommodates not only the "moral virtues" but also the "natural abilities" of the mind, and by downplaying the distinction as not very important and largely a matter of mere terminology.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Virtues and abilities are alike, Hume contends, in their "causes and effects": they are mental qualities that produce pleasure and elicit approval, and we all care about both.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] To the objection that the distinction matters because the approval of abilities feels different from the approval of virtues, Hume responds that our approval of different things always feels different (e.g., with different virtues).
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] These natural abilities of the mind are valued mainly for their usefulness for the person himself: e.g. prudence, sagacity, industry, patience.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Sometimes immediate agreeableness is most important, whether to others (e.g. wit, eloquence, charisma, even cleanliness) or the person himself (e.g. cheerfulness).
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Our judgements are influenced by empirical associations between a quality and a person's age or walk of life (e.g., disapproval of levity in the old).
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Natural abilities also influence our evaluations by making an able person more consequential in life, for good or ill.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Thus far Hume's account has dealt exclusively with mental qualities, but he goes some way to accommodate "bodily advantages" and "the advantages of *fortune*", which are equally capable of eliciting "love and approbation".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Thus women love a strong man in sympathy with the utility a lover of his could be expected to receive, everyone finds beauty in healthy and useful body parts, and an immediate pleasure or dismay arises from the perception of regular features or "a sickly air", respectively.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Thus we esteem the wealthy by sympathy with the pleasure their riches give them, reinforced by their being more consequential.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Hume notes that, though he cannot explain why, the feeling of approval is more determined by the kind of subject contemplated (e.g., an inanimate object, or a person) than by the kind of mechanism driving the approval (e.g., sympathy with utility, or immediate agreeableness).
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] The conclusion of Book 3, and therefore the *Treatise* as a whole, briefly recapitulates the reasoning for Hume's thesis that "sympathy is the chief source of moral distinctions".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Indeed, most would agree that justice and "the useful qualities of the mind" are valued for their usefulness, and what besides sympathy can explain why we care about the public good or "the happiness of strangers"?
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] This "system of ethics" is not only supported by "solid argument", Hume adds, but it can help moralists show the "*dignity*" and the "*happiness*" of virtue.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] First, it puts morality in a good light to see it derived from "so noble a source" as sympathy: we end up approving of virtue, the sense of virtue, and even the psychological principles underlying the sense of virtue.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Secondly, a life of virtue pays off quite well, bringing immediate advantages, an enhanced social reputation, and the "inward satisfaction" of a mind able to "bear its own survey".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] So, while Hume presents himself as a theoretical "anatomist" who dissects human psychology into ugly bits, his work is well-suited for the practical "painter" who styles morality into a beautiful and inviting ideal.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] The *Treatise* has appeared in many editions since the death of the author.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Hume's *Treatise* inspired Albert Einstein, who in a 1915 letter explained "The theory of relativity suggests itself in positivism.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] Öcalan was based in Syria from 1979 to 1998.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] He helped found the PKK in 1978, and led it into the Kurdish–Turkish conflict in 1984.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] For most of his leadership, he was based in Syria, which provided sanctuary to the PKK until the late 1990s.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] The sentence was commuted to aggravated life imprisonment when Turkey abolished the death penalty.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] From 1999 until 2009, he was the sole prisoner in İmralı prison in the Sea of Marmara, where he is still held.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] Öcalan has advocated for a political solution to the conflict since the 1993 Kurdistan Workers' Party ceasefire. Öcalan's prison regime has oscillated between long periods of isolation during which he is allowed no contact with the outside world, and periods when he is permitted visits.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] He was also involved in negotiations with the Turkish government that led to a temporary Kurdish–Turkish peace process in 2013.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] In February 2025, he issued a statement from prison calling on the PKK to disarm and disband itself, after which the group's leadership declared a unilateral ceasefire.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] From prison, Öcalan has published several books.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] While some sources report his date of birth as 4 April 1949, no official birth records exist.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] He has claimed not to know exactly when he was born, estimating the year to be 1946 or 1947.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] He is the oldest of seven children. Öcalan's father was poor even by local standards, and he once said that there was "always fighting" and "an overwhelming unhappiness" in his family.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] When asked about their ethnic origin, his younger brother Osman Öcalan stated that their paternal family was fully Kurdish, while their maternal family was of mixed Kurdish, Turkish, Arab, and Assyrian origins.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] While Abdullah Öcalan claimed that their mother was fully Turkmen, Osman Öcalan disputed it, stating that many Albanian and other Balkan migrants were imported to the region by the Ottomans and identified as Turks, although he did not fully dismiss the possibility of their mother being Turkish.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] After the death of Abdi Ağa, Hüseyin Ağa led more revenge attacks on the Ottomans and drove them away.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] The family was celebrated by other Kurds and known as "Mala Ocê" ("House of Revenge").
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] After the Surname Law, the surname was Turkified to "Öcalan", meaning "revengeful".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] Abdullah Öcalan spoke only Kurdish until elementary school, which he attended in a neighboring village.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] After he began school, he learned Turkish and began assimilating.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] He was impacted by Turkish nationalist school curriculum and dreamed of joining the Turkish army when he grew up.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] He applied to a military high school for future commissioned officers, but had failed the admission exam.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] Rejected from the military high school, Öcalan enrolled in a vocational high school in Ankara (Turkish: *Ankara Tapu-Kadastro Meslek Lisesi*) in 1966.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] After graduating in 1969, Öcalan began working at the Title Deeds Office of Diyarbakır.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] It was at this time his political affiliation began to reform.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] He was relocated one year later to Istanbul where he participated in the meetings of the Revolutionary Cultural Eastern Hearths (DDKO), a Kurdish organization.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] Later, he entered the Istanbul Law Faculty but after the first year transferred to Ankara University to study political science.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] According to a book by journalist Necdet Pekmezci, Öcalan's return to Ankara was facilitated by the state in order to divide the *Dev-Genç* (Revolutionary Youth Federation of Turkey), of which Öcalan was a member.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] President Süleyman Demirel later regretted this decision, since the PKK was to become a much greater threat to the state than *Dev-Genç*.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] Öcalan was not able to graduate from Ankara University, as on 7 April 1972 he was arrested after participating in a rally against the killing of Mahir Çayan.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] He was charged with distributing the left-wing political magazine *Şafak* (published by Doğu Perinçek) and was held for seven months at the Mamak Prison.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] In November 1973, the Ankara Democratic Association of Higher Education, (*Ankara Demokratik Yüksek Öğrenim Demeği,* ADYÖD) was founded and shortly after he was elected to join its board.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] In the ADYÖD several students close to the political views of Hikmet Kıvılcımlı were active.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] In December 1974, *ADYÖD* was closed down.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] In 1975, together with Mazlum Doğan and Mehmet Hayri Durmuş, he published a political booklet which described the main aims for a *Revolution in Kurdistan*.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] During meetings in Ankara between 1974 and 1975, Öcalan and others came to the conclusion that Kurdistan was a colony and preparations ought to be made for a revolution.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] The group decided to disperse into the different towns in Turkish Kurdistan in order to set up a base of supporters for an armed revolution.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] At the beginning, this idea had only a few supporters, but following a journey Öcalan made through the cities of Ağrı, Batman, Diyarbakır, Bingöl, Kars and Urfa in 1977, the group counted over 300 adherents and had organised about thirty armed militants.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] In 1978, in the midst of the right- and left-wing conflicts which culminated in the 1980 Turkish coup d'état, Öcalan founded the Kurdistan Workers' Party (PKK).
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] Since its foundation, the party focused on ideological training.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] "If you break the link between yourself and ideology you will beastialize," he told his followers.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] With the support of the Syrian Government, he established two training camps for the PKK in Lebanon where the Kurdish guerrillas should receive political and military training.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] In 1984, the PKK initiated a campaign of armed conflict by attacking government forces in order to create an independent Kurdish state. Öcalan attempted to unite the Kurdish liberation movements of the PKK and the one active against Saddam Hussein in Iraq.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] In negotiations between the Kurdistan Democratic Party (KDP) and the PKK, it was agreed that the latter was able to move freely in Iraqi Kurdistan.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] He also met twice with Masoud Barzani, the leader of the KDP in Damascus, to resolve some minor issues they had once in 1984 and another time in 1985.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] But due to pressure from Turkey the cooperation remained timid.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] During an interview he gave to the Turkish Milliyet in 1988, he mentioned the goal wasn't to gain independence from Turkey at all costs, but remained firm on the issue of the Kurdish rights, and suggested that negotiations should take place for a federation to be established in Turkey.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] In 1988, he also met with Jalal Talabani of the Patriotic Union of Kurdistan (PUK) in Damascus, with which he signed an agreement and after some differences after the foundation of a Kurdish Government in Iraqi Kurdistan in 1992 he later had a better relationship.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] In the early 1990s, interviews given to both Doğu Perinçek and Hasan Bildirici he mentioned his willingness to achieve a peaceful solution to the conflict.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] In another given to Oral Çalışlar, he emphasized the difference between independence and separatism.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] He articulated the view that different nations were able to live in independence within the same state if they had equal rights.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] Then in 1993, upon request of Turkish president Turgut Özal, Öcalan met with Jalal Talabani for negotiations following which Öcalan declared a unilateral cease fire which had a duration from 20 March to 15 April.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] Later he prolonged it in order to enable negotiations with the Turkish government.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] Soon after Özal died on 17 April 1993, the initiative was halted by Turkey on the grounds that Turkey did not negotiate with terrorists.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] During an International Kurdish Conference in Brussels in March 1994, his initiative for equal rights for Kurds and Turks within Turkey was discussed.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] It is reported by Gottfried Stein, that at least during the first half of the 1990s, he used to live mainly in a protected neighborhood in Damascus.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] On 7 May 1996, in the midst of another unilateral cease-fire declared by the PKK, an attempt to assassinate him in a house in Damascus, was unsuccessful.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] Following the protests which arose against the prohibition of the PKK in Germany, Öcalan had several meetings with politicians from Germany who came to hold talks with him.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] Back in Germany, Lummer made a statement in support for further negotiations with Öcalan.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] With time, the United States (1997), European Union, Syria, Turkey, and other countries have included the PKK on their lists of terrorist organizations.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] A Greek parliamentary delegation from the PASOK came to visit him in the Beqaa valley on 17 October 1996.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] During his stay in Syria he has published several books concerning the Kurdish revolution.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] On at least one occasion, in 1993, he was detained and held by Syria's General Intelligence Directorate, but later released.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] As the situation deteriorated in Turkey, the Turkish government openly threatened Syria over its support for the PKK.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] As a result, the Syrian government forced Öcalan to leave the country but still refused turning him over to the Turkish authorities.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] In October 1998, Öcalan prepared for his departure from Syria and during a meeting in Kobane, he unsuccessfully attempted to lay the foundations for a new party which failed due to Syrian intelligence's obstruction.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] Öcalan left Syria on 9 October 1998 and for the next four months, he toured several European countries advocating for a solution of the Kurdish-Turkish conflict. Öcalan first went to Russia where the Russian parliament voted on 4 November 1998 to grant him asylum.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] On 6 November 109 Greek parliamentarians invited Öcalan to stay in Greece, a move which was repeated by Panayioitis Sgouridis, the deputy speaker of the Greek Parliament at the time. Öcalan then chose to travel to Italy, where he landed on 12 November 1998 at the airport in Rome.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] In 1998 the Turkish government requested the extradition of Öcalan from Italy, where he applied for political asylum upon his arrival.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] He was detained by the Italian authorities due to an arrest warrant issued by Germany.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] But Italy did not extradite him to Germany, who refused to hold a trial on Öcalan in its country.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] The German chancellor Gerhard Schröder as well as the Minister of the Interior Otto Schily preferred that Öcalan would be tried by an unspecified "European Court".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] Italy also didn't extradite him to Turkey.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] The Italian prime minister Massimo D'Alema announced it was contrary to Italian law to extradite someone to a country where the defendant is threatened with a capital punishment.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] But Italy also didn't want Öcalan to stay, and pulled several diplomatic strings to compel him to leave the country, which was accomplished on 16 January when he departed to Nizhny Novgorod in hope to find a safe haven in Russia.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] But in Russia he was not as much welcomed as in October, and he had to wait for a week at the airport of Strigino International Airport in Nizhny Novgorod.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] From Russia, he took an airplane from Saint Petersburg to Greece where he arrived in Athens upon the invitation of Nikolas Naxakis, a retired Admiral on 29 January 1999.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] He spent the night as a guest of the popular Greek author Voula Damianakou in Nea Makri.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] At that time he was defended by Britta Böhler, a high-profile German attorney who argued that the crimes he was accused of would have to be proven in court and attempted to reach that the International Court in The Hague would assume the case.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] Öcalan was abducted in Kenya on 15 February 1999, while on his way from the Greek embassy to Jomo Kenyatta International Airport in Nairobi, in an operation by the Turkish National Intelligence Organization (Turkish: *Millî İstihbarat Teşkilatı**,* MIT), with the help of the CIA.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] Following his capture, the Greek Government was in turmoil and Foreign Minister Theodoros Pangalos, Interior Minister Alekos Papadopoulos and the Minister of Public Order Philipos Petsalnikos resigned from their posts.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] Costoulas, the Greek ambassador who protected him, said that his own life was in danger after the operation.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] Kurds living in Germany were threatened with deportation if they continued to hold demonstrations in support of Öcalan.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] The warning came after three Kurds were killed and 16 injured during the 1999 attack on the Israeli consulate in Berlin.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] A group named the *Revenge Hawks of Apo* set fire to a department store in Kadıköy Istanbul, causing the death of 13 people.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] In several European capitals and larger cities as well as in Iraq, Iran and also Turkey protests were organized against his capture.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] He was brought to İmralı island, where he was interrogated for a period of 10 days without being allowed to see or speak to his lawyers.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] A state security court consisting of one military and two civilian judges was established on İmralı island to try Öcalan.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] A delegation of three Dutch lawyers who intended to defend him were not allowed to meet with their client and detained for questioning at the airport on the grounds that they acted as "PKK militants" and not lawyers; they were sent back to the Netherlands.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] On the seventh day a judge took part in the interrogations, and prepared a transcript of it.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] The trial began on 31 May 1999 on the İmralı island in the Sea of Marmara, and was organized by the Ankara State Security Court.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] During the trial, he was represented by the Asrın Law Office.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] His lawyers had difficulty in representing him adequately as they were allowed only two interviews per week of initially a duration of 20 minutes, and later 1 hour, of which several were cancelled due to "bad weather" or because the authorities didn't give the permission needed for them.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] Also his lawyers were unaware of what the charges might be, and received the formal indictment only after excerpts of it were already presented to the press.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] The trial was accompanied by arrests of scores of Kurdish politicians from the People's Democracy Party (HADEP).
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] In mid-June 1999, the Grand National Assembly of Turkey approved the removal of military judges from the State Security Courts, in an attempt to address criticism from the European Court of Human Rights and a civilian judge assumed the post of the military judge.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] Shortly before the verdict was read out by Judge Turgut Okyay, when asked about his final remarks, he again offered to play a role in the peace finding process. Öcalan was charged with treason and separatism and sentenced to death on 29 June 1999.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] He was also banned from holding public office for life.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] On the same day, Amnesty International (AI) demanded a re-trial and Human Rights Watch (HRW) questioned the fact that witnesses brought by the defense were not heard in the trial.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] In 1999 the Turkish Parliament discussed a so-called Repentance Bill which would commute Öcalans death sentence to 20 years imprisonment and allow PKK militants to surrender with a limited amnesty, but it didn't pass due to resistance from the far-right around the Nationalist Movement Party (MHP).
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] In January 2000 the Turkish government declared the death sentence was delayed until the European Court of Human Rights (ECHR) reviewed the verdict.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] Upon the abolition of the death penalty in Turkey in August 2002, in October of that year, the security court commuted his sentence to life imprisonment.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] In an attempt to reach a verdict which was more favorable to Öcalan, he appealed at the ECHR at Strasbourg, which accepted the case in June 2004.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] In 2005, the ECHR ruled that Turkey had violated articles 3, 5, and 6 of the European Convention of Human Rights by refusing to allow Öcalan to appeal his arrest and by sentencing him to death without a fair trial. Öcalan's request for a retrial was refused by Turkish courts.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] After his capture, Öcalan was held in solitary confinement as the only prisoner on İmralı island in the Sea of Marmara.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] Following the commutation of the death sentence to a life sentence in 2002, Öcalan remained imprisoned on İmralı, and was the sole inmate there.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] Although former prisoners at İmralı were transferred to other prisons, more than 1,000 Turkish military personnel were stationed on the island to guard him.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] In November 2009, Turkish authorities announced that they were ending his solitary confinement by transferring several other prisoners to İmralı.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] They said that Öcalan would be allowed to see them for ten hours a week.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] The new prison was built after the Council of Europe's Committee for the Prevention of Torture visited the island and objected to the conditions in which he was being held.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] From 27 July 2011 until 2 May 2019 his lawyers have not been allowed to see Abdullah Öcalan.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] From July 2011 until December 2017 his lawyers filed more than 700 appeals for visits, but all were rejected.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] There have been held regular demonstrations by the Kurdish community to raise awareness of the isolation of Öcalan.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] In October 2012 several hundred Kurdish political prisoners went on hunger strike for better detention conditions for Öcalan and the right to use the Kurdish language in education and jurisprudence.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] The hunger strike lasted 68 days until Öcalan demanded its end. Öcalan was banned from receiving visits almost two years from 6 October 2014 until 11 September 2016, when his brother Mehmet Öcalan visited him for Eid al-Adha.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] In 2014 the ECHR ruled in that there was a violation of article 3 in regards of him being to only prisoner on İmarli island until 17 November 2009, as well as the impossibility to appeal his verdict.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] On 6 September 2018 visits from lawyers were banned for six months due to former punishments he received in the years 2005–2009, the fact that the lawyers made their conversations with Ocalan public, and the impression that Öcalan was leading the PKK through communications with his lawyers.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] He was again banned from receiving visits until 12 January 2019 when his brother was permitted to visit him a second time.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] The ban on the visitation of his lawyers was lifted in April 2019, and Öcalan saw his lawyers on 2 May 2019.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] In January 1999 during his stay in Europe, Öcalan saw the parties liberation struggle focus to have developed from guerrilla warfare to dialogue and negotiations.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] After his capture Öcalan called for a halt in PKK attacks, and advocated for a peaceful solution for the Kurdish conflict inside the borders of Turkey.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] In October 1999, eight PKK militants around the former European PKK spokesman Ali Sapan turned themselves in to Turkey on request of Öcalan.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] Depending on their treatment, the other PKK militants would turn themselves in as well, his attorney announced.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] A similar structure began functioning in May 2006.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] With this process, the way to democratic dialogue will be also opened".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] Though the Turkish government had received Öcalan's protocols, they were never released to the public. Öcalan said he would leave the top PKK commanders in charge of the conflict, but that this should not be misinterpreted as a call for the PKK to intensify its armed conflict with Turkey.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] In January 2013, peace negotiations between the PKK and the Turkish Government were initiated and from between January and March he met several times with politicians of Peace and Democracy Party (BDP) on Imralı Island.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] On 21 March, Öcalan declared a ceasefire between the PKK and the Turkish state. Öcalan's statement was read to hundreds of thousands of Kurds in Diyarbakır who had gathered to celebrate the Kurdish New Year (*Newroz*).
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] The statement said in part, "Let guns be silenced and politics dominate... a new door is being opened from the process of armed conflict to democratization and democratic politics.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] It's the start of a new era." Soon after Öcalan's declaration, the functional head of the PKK, Murat Karayılan responded by promising to implement a ceasefire.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] During the peace process, the pro-Kurdish Peoples' Democratic Party (HDP) entered parliament during the parliamentarian election of June 2015.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] The ceasefire ended following the 2014 Kobanî protests and after two Turkish police officers were killed in Ceylanpınar in July 2015, leading to the 2015–2016 Kurdish–Turkish conflict.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] On 27 February 2025, Öcalan issued a message from prison calling for the PKK to hold a congress dissolving itself and lay down its weapons, kicking off the 2025 PKK–Turkey peace process.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] In response, the PKK announced that it had begun a ceasefire on 1 March.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] Following the PKK's decision to dissolve itself in May 2025, Öcalan issued a message the following month announcing the end of the PKK insurgency against the Turkish state.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] Since his incarceration, Öcalan has significantly changed his ideology through exposure to Western social theorists such as Murray Bookchin, Immanuel Wallerstein and Hannah Arendt.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] Abandoning his old Marxism–Leninist and Stalinist beliefs, Öcalan fashioned his ideal society called democratic confederalism.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] In early 2004, Öcalan attempted to arrange a meeting with Murray Bookchin through Öcalan's lawyers, describing himself as Bookchin's "student" eager to adapt Bookchin's thought to Middle Eastern society.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] Bookchin was too ill to meet with Öcalan.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] In this zone, three bodies of law would be implemented: EU law, Turkish/Syrian/Iraqi/Iranian law and Kurdish law.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] While some of his followers questioned Öcalan's conversion from Marxism-Leninism to social ecology, the PKK adopted Öcalan's proposal and began to form assemblies.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] All are welcome to partake in the communal councils, but political participation is not mandated.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] There is no private property, but rather "ownership by use, which grants individuals usage rights to the buildings, land, and infrastructure, but not the right to sell and buy on the market or convert them to private enterprises".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] The economy is in the hands of the communal councils, and is thus (in the words of Bookchin) 'neither collectivised nor privatised - it is common.' Feminism, ecology, and direct democracy are essential in democratic confederalism.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] Parallel to Democratic Confederalism, Öcalan introduced the principle of the Brotherhood of Peoples in 2013, aimed at promoting peaceful coexistence between Kurds and other ethnic groups, similar to the Marxist concept of the friendship of peoples.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] During the 2025 PKK–Turkey peace process, Öcalan repeatedly emphasized the Brotherhood of Peoples, stating that it had "reached a threshold" and referring to a "1000-year-old" historical brotherhood between Kurds and Turks.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] Öcalan is a supporter of the liberation of the women, he writes in his Freedom Manifesto for Women that all slavery is based on the housewifization of women.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] He deems the woman often as being trapped in a situation where she accepts traditional gender roles and a disadvantaged relationship with a man.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] In the context of Turkey and the activities of the HDP, and now DEM Party, this approach has been described by as Turkeyification, which critics characterize as a form of voluntary Turkification.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] The Middle East Forum described Öcalan's stance in the 2025 PKK–Turkey peace process as paradoxical, noting that the PKK was originally founded in response to the denial of Kurdish existence in Turkey.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] Öcalan's Brotherhood of Peoples concept has also faced similar criticism.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] Some commentators have described it as a "project that was born rejected," particularly after Arab tribes defected from the Kurdish-led Syrian Democratic Forces (SDF) during the 2026 northeastern Syria offensive, which may have contributed to the collapse of the DAANES.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] During Öcalan's childhood, his mother, Esma Öcalan (Uveys) was rather dominant and criticised his father, blaming him for their dire economic situation.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] He later explained in an interview that it was in his childhood he learned to defend himself from injustice.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] Like many Kurds in Turkey, Öcalan was raised speaking Turkish; according to Amikam Nachmani, lecturer at the Bar-Ilan University in Israel, Öcalan did not know Kurdish when he met him in 1991.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] Nachmani: "*He [Öcalan] told me that he speaks Turkish, gives orders in Turkish, and thinks in Turkish."* In 1978 Öcalan married Kesire Yildirim, who he had met at the Ankara University and was of a better household than the regular revolutionaries around Öcalan.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] They had a difficult marriage with reportedly many disputes and discussions.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] In 1988, while representing the PKK in Athens, Greece, his wife unsuccessfully attempted to overthrow Öcalan, following which Yildirim went underground.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] After his sister Havva was married to a man from another village in an arranged marriage, he felt regret.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] This event led Öcalan to his policies towards the liberation of women from the traditional suppressed female role. Öcalan's brother Osman became a PKK commander until he defected from the PKK with several others to establish the Patriotic and Democratic Party of Kurdistan.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] His other brother, Mehmet Öcalan, is a member of the pro-Kurdish Peace and Democracy Party (BDP).
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] Fatma Öcalan is the sister of Abdullah Öcalan and Dilek Öcalan, a former parliamentarian of the HDP, is his niece. Ömer Öcalan, a current member of parliament for the HDP, is his nephew.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] Öcalan is the author of more than 40 books, four of which were written in prison.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] Many of the notes taken from his weekly meetings with his lawyers have been edited and published.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/abdullah-öcalan] He has also written articles for the newspaper Özgür Gündem which is a newspaper that reported on the Kurdish-Turkish conflict, under the pseudonym of Ali Firat.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] In ethics and governance, **accountability** is equated with answerability, culpability, liability, and the expectation of account-giving.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] As in an aspect of governance, it has been central to discussions related to problems in the public sector, nonprofit, private (corporate), and individual contexts.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] In leadership roles, accountability is the acknowledgment of and assumption of responsibility for actions, products, decisions, and policies such as administration, governance, and implementation, including the obligation to report, justify, and be answerable for resulting consequences.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] In governance, accountability has expanded beyond the basic definition of "being called to account for one's actions".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] It is frequently described as an account-giving relationship between individuals, e.g.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Accountability cannot exist without proper accounting practices; in other words, an absence of accounting means an absence of accountability.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Another key area that contributes to accountability is good records management.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] The word *accountability* derives from the late Latin *accomptare* (to account), a prefixed form of *computare* (to calculate), which in turn is derived from *putare* (to reckon).
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] While the word itself does not appear in English until its use in 13th century Norman England, the concept of account-giving has ancient roots in record-keeping activities related to governance and money-lending systems that first developed in Ancient Egypt, Israel, Babylon, Greece, and later Rome.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] The scientific literature identifies several forms of accountability, which can be referred to as accountability modes.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Administrative accountability refers to how public administrators monitor each other through various mechanisms.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Political accountability is when a politician makes choices on behalf of the people, and the people have the ability to reward or sanction the politician.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] In representative democracies, citizens delegate power to elected officials through periodic elections, and such officials are empowered to represent or act in the citizens' interest.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] A challenge is how to see to it that those with such power, who presumably have divergent interests from the citizens, nonetheless act in their best interests.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Citizens can rely on rewards or sanctions to reward or threaten politicians who might otherwise act in a manner that is antithetical to the people's interest.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Accountability occurs when citizens only vote to re-elect representatives who act in their interests, and if representatives then select policies that will help them be re-elected.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Representatives can be held accountable through two mechanisms: electoral replacement and rational anticipation.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] In electoral replacement, citizens vote to replace representatives who are out of step with their interests.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Rational anticipation requires that representatives anticipate the consequences of being out of step with their constituency and then govern in accordance with citizens' wishes to avoid negative consequences.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Accountability can still be achieved even if citizens are not perfectly knowledgeable about their representatives' actions; as long as representatives believe that they will be held accountable by citizens, they will still be motivated to act in accordance with the citizens' interests.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Electoral accountability refers to citizens using their vote to sanction or reward politicians.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Some researchers have considered accountability using formal theory, which makes assumptions about the state of the world to draw larger conclusions.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Voters can hold representatives accountable through the process of sanctioning—voting the incumbent out of office in response to poor performance.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] While politicians face a decrease in vote share as a result of poor performance, they are less likely to see an increase in vote share for good performance.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Selection—voters choosing candidates based on who will best represent their interests—is another method by which voters hold their representatives accountable.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] These methods of accountability can occur simultaneously, with voters holding representatives accountable using both sanctioning and selection.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] These conclusions rely on the assumption that voters do not observe the policy implemented by the incumbent, but do know their own welfare.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Some factors make it harder for voters to sanction incumbents.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] When politicians do not have control over outcomes, it becomes harder to hold them accountable.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Additionally, when organizations are unable to monitor elections and provide information to voters, then voters struggle to sanction the incumbent.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] When voters are better informed about the incumbent's performance, the incumbent is more vulnerable to voter sanctioning.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Furthermore, when incumbents face sanctioning, challengers are more likely to enter the race.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] While elections provide a mechanism which can theoretically increase government accountability to citizens, they may instead lead to less egalitarian policy outcomes, because those who hold the government accountable tend to be from wealthier segments of society.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] For example, a study of elected versus appointed property assessors in the state of New York shows that the election of property assessors leads to policies that severely undertax wealthier homes relative to poorer homes.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Studies on political accountability have emphasized the key role of elections in promoting accountability in democratic settings.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] It is through elections that citizens hold governments accountable for past performance.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] The role of elections in fostering accountability is often undermined by electoral manipulation and fraud.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] By preventing citizens from removing leaders through elections based on their performance in office, electoral manipulation breaks down accountability and may undercut the consolidation of democratic institutions.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Electoral manipulation is not rare; some estimates are that in the 1990s and 2000s, up to one fourth of elections suffered some form of substantial manipulation.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] This includes a large array of pre-election and election-day tactics, such as outlawing rival parties and candidates, employing violence and intimidation, and manipulating voter registration and vote count.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Some efforts to improve accountability by preventing electoral manipulation and fraud have obtained a certain measure of success, such as using cell phone applications for monitoring and disseminating polling station results and employing domestic or international election observers.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] However, governments may simply alter the type of manipulation or where it occurs in order to deceive observers and monitoring agencies.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Governments, politicians, and political parties are more likely to resort to electoral manipulation and fraud when they believe they might be removed from office and when they face few institutional constraints to their power.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Low political competition has also been linked to some forms of manipulation, such as abolishing presidential term limits.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Well-connected candidates are more likely to resort to vote count fraud.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Governments may engage in electoral manipulation not only to obtain victory at a given election or to remain in office longer, but also for post-election reasons, such as reducing the strength of the opposition or increasing their own bargaining power in the subsequent period.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Politicians may be incentivized to provide common goods as a means of accountability.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] The ability of voters to attribute the credit and blame of outcomes also determines the extent of public goods provision.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Research suggests that public goods provision is conditional on being able to attribute outcomes to politicians as opposed to civil servants.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] This attribution can be enhanced by more short-run and visible inputs and outcomes such as famine relief or access to drinking water, whereas lower-visibility issues such as sanitation and education may be more difficult to attribute credit for and thus less likely to provide for.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Another condition determining how voters use the provision of public goods to hold leaders accountable is whether the prioritization of public goods is determined either directly via vote or delegated to a governing body.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] A 2016 experiment in Afghanistan regarding rural development projects, however, finds that when voters directly prioritize their preferences at the ballot box, they perceive the quality of local government to be higher than when a governing committee prioritizes development projects.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Other research indicates that voters use elections to hold politicians accountable for the provision of public goods.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] In India, rural areas are charged a flat rate for electricity, but in the province of Uttar Pradesh, line loss—electricity that is consumed but not billed—is significantly higher in election years than non-election years, and increases in line loss reliably predict electoral gains.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Voters rewarded incumbent politicians with a 12% increase in party seats in response to a 10% increase of unbilled electricity, in 2007 elections.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] In Ghana, the improvement of road conditions is linked to an increasing vote share for incumbent parties.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Both of these research outcomes hinge on voters being able to attribute the service of public goods to politicians.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Politicians may also have incentives to respond to pressure for public goods provision in electoral autocracies.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] There is evidence that as autocratic governments lose seats in their party's legislatures, they respond by increasing spending on public goods such as education, healthcare, and pensions.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] While the introduction of elections is generally thought to improve public goods provision, in some cases, researchers have shown that it may reduce its quality.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Governments are held accountable if citizens can punish or reward the government to influence it to pursue their best interests.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Political changes after protests can be the result of the protests *per se*, or symptoms of shifts in political preferences underneath the observable phenomena of the protests.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] One study of the Tea Party movement in the United States has shown that protests *per se* have an impact on political change.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Other scholars studied the effect of protests on political changes in developing countries.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Mass protests instigated by economic hardship and political repression occurred in 16 sub-Saharan African countries, and 21 governments in the region implemented significant political reforms, such as the adoption of multi-party elections.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Authoritarian regimes in Africa distorted the market and reduced the cost of farm produce in favor of urban workers at the cost of rural farmers in the 1980s to prevent urban unrest, which is more visible and easier to mobilize than rural protests.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Selectorates are those on whom a leader depends in order to hold onto power, and those who have the ability to depose a leader.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] When a selectorate's hold on power is not overly dependent on the leader in office, selectorates can remove poorly performing leaders, and this accountability by selectorates renders it possible for autocracies to perform better for the benefit of all.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Beyond that, institutions can act as credible restraints on autocracy as well.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] In democracies, voluntary associations, interest groups, and associational activity can improve the performance of the government.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] One study showed that civil society organizations such as NGOs can increase the performance of local government according to the central government's standards by monitoring and disclosing information about local government performance in authoritarian regimes like China.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Solidarity groups in rural China, in which members share moral obligations and interests, can hold local officials accountable as well when (i) the solidarity group encompasses everyone under the local government's jurisdiction, and (ii) local officials are embedded in the group as members.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] The social standing and recognition of these groups encourages local officials to perform well, as they value high moral standing in the group.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] At the local level, various accountability measures exist that impact the job performance of elected officials.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] In Uganda, civil society organizations (CSOs) that divulge to the public how well an incumbent is performing their job duties, in a district with an upcoming competitive election, increase the performance of the politician for the rest of their term.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] In contrast to these works, a meta-analysis released in 2019 uncovers no effects from CSO voter information campaigns on political accountability after examining the results from seven trials across six countries.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Additionally, many local elections are for positions that involve performing jobs with a single function, such as a school board member or a sheriff.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] These elected officials are held accountable to their positions mainly through information provided to the public through the media.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] When the media focuses attention on data trends associated with these positions, constituents are then able to use this information to retrospectively vote for or against an incumbent based on their performance in office.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Approval ratings generated through public opinion polling create a measure of job performance during an incumbent's term that has implications for whether the official will retain their seat, or if reelection will even be sought.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] These approval ratings predict election outcomes when combined with other factors included in Bayesian Model Averaging forecasts.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] In the United States, senator job approval ratings affect whether a senator will retire, the quality of candidates that seek to challenge them, the amount of money the senator can raise to seek reelection if they decide to run, and the outcome of the election itself.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Strategic incumbent senators will seek reelection less when their approval ratings are low during their time in office.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Traditional leaders in Zambia provide local public goods despite the fact that they lack an electoral incentive to do so.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Political corruption refers to "the misuse or the abuse of public office for private gains".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Corrupt practices include fraud, appropriation of public funds, and accepting bribes.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Corruption can cause people to negatively evaluate politicians, since citizens may perceive corruption as a signal of poor performance, motivating them to sanction an incumbent.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] As the model of retrospective voting suggests that voters incentivize good politicians' behavior by rewarding good performance and punishing bad performance, citizens are expected to sanction corrupt politicians.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] However, studies suggest that though voters have a distaste for corruption, they often fail to punish corrupt incumbents; some of them receive benefits from their representatives' corrupt practices, and prefer to retain this type of politician.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] In high-corruption contexts, voters may become more tolerant of or even prefer corrupt politicians because others are also perceived as corrupt, leading to a corrupt equilibrium "where voters are generally willing to retain corrupt politicians", referred to as a "political corruption trap".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] This high corruption equilibrium is difficult to break due to interaction between corrupt politicians, voters who tolerate and retain corrupt politicians, and potential entrants or challengers who also engage in corrupt practices, leading to the maintenance of corruption.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Economic development is associated with a decrease in corruption.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Freedom of the press contributes to the reduction of corruption by exposing corrupt actions.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Documentation on how a corrupt government (e.g.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Alberto Fujimori's government from 1998 to 2000 in Peru) can strategically undermine checks-and-balances institutions, suggests that the news media—i.e. newspapers and mainly television—is crucial to the dissemination of information to the public.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] There is also evidence about the importance of local media, such as local radio stations, in holding corrupt incumbents accountable and in promoting non-corrupt politicians.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Information about corruption may not only lead to vote losses for the incumbent parties, but also for challenging parties, as well the erosion of partisan attachments, which implies that information about corruption also provokes citizens' disengagement from the political process.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Scholarly literature about corruption finds mixed results about the role of political institutions on the level of a country's corruption.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] For example, some scholarly research suggests that more horizontal accountability, or oversight across branches of government, would generally decrease corruption.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Low accountability for corruption is difficult to combat, and some anti-corruption activities may also lead to perverse consequences.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] For example, in places where private sector work pays better than public sector work (e.g., China), highly qualified individuals engaging in public sector work may only find such work attractive because it allows for further compensation through corrupt activities.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Government anti-corruption activities can therefore decrease the quality and overall representativeness of the bureaucracy as a result.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] On the other hand, there is evidence that, despite strategic evasion and unintentional consequences, anti-corruption initiatives are beneficial, as they lower malfeasance and increase social welfare, even where strategic evasion is relatively large.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Police accountability involves holding both individual police officers and law enforcement agencies responsible for effectively delivering basic crime control services and maintaining order, while treating individuals fairly and within the bounds of the law.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Police are expected to uphold laws, regarding due process, search and seizure, arrests, discrimination, as well as other laws relating to equal employment, sexual harassment, etc.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Holding police accountable is important for maintaining the public's "faith in the system".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Research has shown that the public prefers independent review of complaints against law enforcement, rather than relying on police departments to conduct internal investigations.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Public perception of police accountability can be partisan.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Electoral accountability can improve police accountability of asset forfeiture.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Within an organization, the principles and practices of ethical accountability aim to improve both the internal standard of individual and group conduct as well as external factors, such as sustainable economic and ecologic strategies.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Also, ethical accountability plays an important role in academic fields, such as laboratory experiments and field research.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Debates around the practice of ethical accountability on the part of researchers in the social field – whether professional or others – were explored by Norma R.A.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Romm in her work on *Accountability in Social Research*, and elsewhere.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Researcher accountability implies that researchers are cognizant of, and take some responsibility for, the potential impact of their ways of doing research – and of writing it up – on the social fields of which the research is part.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Accountability is linked to considering carefully, and being open to challenge in relation to, one's choices concerning how research agendas are framed and the styles in which research results are written.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] The traceability of actions performed on a system to a specific system entity (user, process, device) also affects accountability.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] For example, the use of unique user identification and authentication supports accountability, and the use of shared user IDs and passwords degrades accountability.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Because many individuals in large organizations contribute in many ways to decisions and policies, it is difficult even in principle to identify who should be accountable for the results.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] This is what is known, following Dennis F.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Thompson, as "the problem of many hands".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] It creates a dilemma for accountability.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] If individuals are held accountable or responsible, individuals who could not have prevented the results are either unfairly punished, or they "take responsibility" in a symbolic ritual without suffering any consequences.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] If only organizations are held accountable, then all individuals in the organization are equally blameworthy or all are excused.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] One is to broaden the criteria for individual responsibility so that individuals are held accountable for not anticipating failures in the organization.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Another solution, recently proposed by Thompson, is to hold individuals accountable for the design of the organization, both retrospectively and prospectively.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Accountability is an element of a responsibility assignment matrix which indicates who is ultimately answerable for the correct and thorough completion of a deliverable or task, as well as the delegation of the work to those responsible.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] With the increase in public service provided by private entities, especially in Britain and the United States, some have called for increased political accountability mechanisms for otherwise non-political entities.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Legal scholar Anne Davies, for instance, argues that the line between public institutions and private entities like corporations is becoming blurred in certain areas of public service in the United Kingdom, and that this can compromise political accountability in those areas.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] She and others argue that some administrative law reform is necessary to address this accountability gap.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] With respect to the public/private overlap in the United States, public concern over the contracting of government services (including military) and the resulting accountability gap was highlighted following the Nisour Square massacre perpetrated by the Blackwater security firm in Iraq.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] As defined by National Council on Measurement in Education (NCME), accountability is "[a] program, often legislated, that attributes the responsibility for student learning to teachers, school administrators, or students.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Student accountability is traditionally based on school and classroom rules, combined with sanctions for infringement.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Freedom of choice, freedom of action, freedom to bear the results of action are considered the three great freedoms that constitute personal responsibility.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Sudbury schools claim that "'Ethics' is a course taught by life experience".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Students are given complete responsibility for their own education and the school is run by a direct democracy in which students and staff are equals.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Econometric research has found that countries with greater press freedom tend to have less corruption.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Greater political accountability and lower corruption were more likely where newspaper consumption was higher, according to data from roughly 100 countries and from different states in the US.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Congressmen who receive less press coverage are less likely to produce a positive impact for their constituencies, are less likely to stand witness before congressional hearings, and federal spending for their district is lower.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] One explanation for the positive impact of media on accountability stems from Besley and Burgess' work.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] They argue that media resolves the information asymmetries between citizens and government and provides a way of overcoming obstacles preventing political action.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] When elected officials and the public gain information, the public is better equipped to hold politicians accountable and politicians are more responsive.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Ferraz & Finan demonstrate this in the Brazilian context.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] In their work, they find releasing audit reports prior to elections creates a more informed electorate which holds incumbent officials accountable.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] While evidence supports the positive impact of press freedom on political accountability, other work highlights the risk of media capture through factors such as media concentration and ownership as government tools for influencing or controlling news content.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Non-democratic regimes use media for a variety of purposes such as – (i) to enhance regime resilience, (ii) censor, or (iii) strategically distract the public.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Control of the media may also be especially beneficial to incumbents in new or developing democracies, who consider media control a spoil of office.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Various systems have been proposed for increasing the funds available for investigative journalism that allow individual citizens to direct small amounts of government funds to news outlets or investigative journalism projects of their choice.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Accountability standards have been established that organizations can voluntarily commit to.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] Standards apply in particular to the non-profit world and to Corporate Social Responsibility initiatives.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/accountability] "principles-based standards to help organisations become more accountable, responsible and sustainable.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] Born in Kirkcaldy, Fife, he studied social philosophy at the University of Glasgow and at the University of Oxford, where he was one of the only students to benefit from scholarships set up by John Snell.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] Following his graduation, he delivered a successful series of public lectures at the University of Edinburgh, that met with acclaim.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] This led to a collaboration with David Hume during the Scottish Enlightenment.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] Smith obtained a professorship at Glasgow, where he taught moral philosophy.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] During this period, he wrote and published *The Theory of Moral Sentiments*.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] Subsequently, he assumed a tutoring position that facilitated travel throughout Europe, where he encountered intellectual figures of his era.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] In response to the prevailing policy of safeguarding national markets and merchants through the reduction of imports and the augmentation of exports, a practice that came to be known as mercantilism, Smith laid the foundational principles of classical free-market economic theory.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] *The Wealth of Nations* was a precursor to the modern academic discipline of economics.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] In this and other works, he developed the concept of division of labour and expounded upon how rational self-interest and competition can lead to economic prosperity.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] Smith was controversial in his day and his general approach and writing style were often satirised by writers such as Horace Walpole.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] Adam Smith was born in Kirkcaldy, in Fife, Scotland.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] His father, Adam Smith senior, was a Scottish Writer to the Signet (senior solicitor), advocate and prosecutor (judge advocate) and also served as comptroller of the customs in Kirkcaldy.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] Smith's mother was born Margaret Douglas, daughter of the landed Robert Douglas of Strathendry, also in Fife; she married Smith's father in 1720.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] Two months before Smith was born, his father died, leaving his mother a widow.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] The date of Smith's baptism into the Church of Scotland at Kirkcaldy was 5 June 1723 and this has often been treated as if it were also his date of birth, which is unknown.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] Although few events in Smith's early childhood are known, the Scottish journalist John Rae, a biographer of Smith, recorded that Smith was abducted by Romani at the age of three and released when others went to rescue him.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] Smith was close to his mother, who probably encouraged him to pursue his scholarly ambitions.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] Smith entered the University of Glasgow at age 14 and studied moral philosophy under Francis Hutcheson.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] Here he developed his passion for the philosophical concepts of reason, civilian liberties and the freedom of speech.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] In 1740 he was the graduate scholar presented to undertake postgraduate studies at the Balliol College of the University of Oxford, under the Snell Exhibition.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] Smith considered the teaching at Glasgow to be far superior to that at Oxford, which he found intellectually stifling.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] According to William Robert Scott, "The Oxford of [Smith's] time gave little if any help towards what was to be his lifework." Nevertheless, he took the opportunity while at Oxford to teach himself several subjects by reading many books from the shelves of the large Bodleian Library.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] When Smith was not studying on his own, his time at Oxford was not a happy one, according to his letters.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] Near the end of his time there, he began suffering from shaking fits, probably the symptoms of a nervous breakdown.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] He left Oxford in 1746, before his scholarship ended.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] Smith's curriculum at Glasgow included logic, metaphysics, moral philosophy, and natural philosophy.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] Under Hutcheson, Smith debated questions of natural justice, fair exchange, and the moral dimensions of commerce; themes which would be reflected in *The Wealth of Nations*.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] Hutcheson argued that workers deserved compensation sufficient to sustain themselves and their families, a concept Smith would later develop into his broader theory of natural wage levels.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] In Book V of *The Wealth of Nations*, Smith comments on the low quality of instruction and the meager intellectual activity at English universities, when compared to their Scottish counterparts.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] Smith began delivering public lectures in 1748 at the University of Edinburgh, sponsored by the Philosophical Society of Edinburgh under the patronage of Lord Kames.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] His lecture topics included rhetoric and *belles-lettres*, and later the subject of "the progress of opulence".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] On this latter topic, he first expounded his economic philosophy of "the obvious and simple system of natural liberty".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] While Smith was not adept at public speaking, his lectures met with success.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] In 1750 Smith met the philosopher David Hume, who was his senior by more than a decade.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] In their writings covering history, politics, philosophy, economics, and religion, Smith and Hume shared closer intellectual and personal bonds than with other important figures of the Scottish Enlightenment.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] In 1751 Smith earned a professorship at Glasgow teaching logic courses, and in 1752, he was elected a member of the Philosophical Society of Edinburgh, having been introduced to the society by Henry Home, Lord Kames.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] The following year, when the position of head of Moral Philosophy in Glasgow became vacant, Smith took over the role.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] He worked as an academic for the next 13 years, which he characterised as "by far the most useful and therefore by far the happiest and most honorable period [of his life]".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] Smith published *The Theory of Moral Sentiments* in 1759, embodying some of his Glasgow lectures.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] This work was concerned with how human morality depends on sympathy between agent and spectator, or the individual and other members of society.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] Smith defined "mutual sympathy" as the basis of moral sentiments.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] Following the publication of *The Theory of Moral Sentiments*, Smith became so popular that many wealthy students left their schools in other countries to enroll at Glasgow to learn under Smith.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] At this time, Smith began to give more attention to jurisprudence and economics in his lectures and less to his theories of morals.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] For example, Smith lectured that the cause of increase in national wealth is labour, rather than the nation's quantity of gold or silver, which is the basis for mercantilism, the economic theory that dominated Western European economic policies at the time.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] In 1762, the University of Glasgow conferred on Smith the title of Doctor of Laws (LL.D.).
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] At the end of 1763, he obtained an offer from the chancellor of the exchequer, Charles Townshend—who had been introduced to Smith by David Hume—to tutor his stepson, Henry Scott, the young Duke of Buccleuch as preparation for a career in international politics.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] Smith resigned from his professorship in 1764 to take the tutoring position.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] He subsequently attempted to return the fees he had collected from his students because he had resigned partway through the term, but his students refused.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] Smith's tutoring job entailed touring Europe with Scott, during which time he educated Scott on a variety of subjects.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] He was paid £300 per year (plus expenses) along with a £300-per-year pension; roughly twice his former income as a teacher.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] Smith first travelled as a tutor to Toulouse, France, where he stayed for a year and a half.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] According to his own account, he found Toulouse to be somewhat boring, having written to Hume that he "had begun to write a book to pass away the time".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] After touring the south of France the group moved to Geneva, where Smith met the French writer and philosopher Voltaire.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] In Paris Smith encountered the Physiocracy school founded by François Quesnay and conversed with their intellectuals.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] Physiocrats were opposed to mercantilism, the dominating economic theory of the time, illustrated in their motto *Laissez faire et laissez passer, le monde va de lui même!* (Let do and let pass, the world goes on by itself!).
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] The wealth of France had been virtually depleted by Louis XIV and Louis XV in ruinous wars, and was further exhausted in aiding the American revolutionary soldiers, against the British.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] In 1766 Henry Scott's younger brother died in Paris, and Smith's tour as a tutor ended shortly thereafter.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] Smith returned home that year to Kirkcaldy, and he devoted much of the next decade to writing his *magnum opus*.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] There, he befriended Henry Moyes, a young blind man who showed precocious aptitude.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] Smith secured the patronage of David Hume and Thomas Reid in the young man's education.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] In May 1767 Smith was elected fellow of the Royal Society of London, and was elected a member of the Literary Club in 1775.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] *The Wealth of Nations* was published in 1776 and was an instant success, selling out its first edition in only six months.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] In 1778 Smith was appointed to a post as commissioner of customs in Scotland and went to live with his mother (who died in 1784) in Panmure House in the Canongate in Edinburgh.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] Five years later, as a member of the Philosophical Society of Edinburgh when it received its royal charter, he automatically became one of the founding members of the Royal Society of Edinburgh.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] From 1787 to 1789 he occupied the honorary position of Lord Rector of the University of Glasgow.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] Smith died in the northern wing of Panmure House in Edinburgh on 17 July 1790 after a painful illness.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] His body was buried in the Canongate Kirkyard.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] On his deathbed, Smith expressed disappointment that he had not achieved more.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] Smith's literary executors were two friends from the Scottish academic world: the physicist and chemist Joseph Black and the pioneering geologist James Hutton.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] Smith left behind many notes and some unpublished material, but gave instructions to destroy anything that was not fit for publication.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] He mentioned an early unpublished *History of Astronomy* as probably suitable, and it duly appeared in 1795, along with other material such as *Essays on Philosophical Subjects*.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] Smith's library went by his will to David Douglas, Lord Reston (son of his cousin Colonel Robert Douglas of Strathendry, Fife), who lived with Smith.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] It was eventually divided between Douglas's two surviving children, Cecilia Margaret (Mrs.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] On the death in 1878 of her husband, the Reverend W.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] The remainder passed to her son, Professor Robert Oliver Cunningham of Queen's College, Belfast, who presented a part to the library of Queen's College.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] After his death, the remaining books were sold.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] Bannerman in 1879, her portion of the library went intact to the New College (of the Free Church) in Edinburgh and the collection was transferred to the University of Edinburgh Main Library in 1972.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] Not much is known about Smith's personal views beyond what can be deduced from his published articles.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] His personal papers were destroyed after his death, per his request.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] He never married, and seems to have maintained a close relationship with his mother, with whom he lived after his return from France and who died six years before him.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] Smith was described by several of his contemporaries and biographers as comically absent-minded, with peculiar habits of speech and gait, and a smile of "inexpressible benignity".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] He was known to talk to himself, a habit that began during his childhood when he would smile in rapt conversation with invisible companions.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] He also had occasional spells of imaginary illness, and he is reported to have had books and papers placed in tall stacks in his study.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] According to one story, Smith took Charles Townshend on a tour of a tanning factory, and while discussing free trade, Smith walked into a huge tanning pit from which he needed help to escape.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] He is also said to have put bread and butter into a teapot, drunk the concoction, and declared it to be the worst cup of tea he had ever had.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] According to another account, Smith distractedly went out walking in his nightgown and ended up 15 miles (24 km) outside town, before nearby church bells brought him back to reality.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] James Boswell, who was a student of Smith's at Glasgow University, and later knew him at the Literary Club, says that Smith thought that speaking about his ideas in conversation might reduce the sale of his books, so his conversation was unimpressive.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] According to Boswell, he once told Sir Joshua Reynolds, that "he made it a rule when in company never to talk of what he understood".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] Smith has been alternatively described as someone who "had a large nose, bulging eyes, a protruding lower lip, a nervous twitch, and a speech impediment" and one whose "countenance was manly and agreeable".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] Smith is said to have acknowledged his looks at one point, saying, "I am a beau in nothing but my books." Smith rarely sat for portraits, so almost all depictions of him created during his lifetime were drawn from memory.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] The best-known portraits of Smith are the profile by James Tassie and two etchings by John Kay.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] The line engravings produced for the covers of 19th-century reprints of *The Wealth of Nations* were based largely on Tassie's medallion.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] Considerable scholarly debate has occurred about the nature of Smith's religious views.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] His father had shown a strong interest in Christianity and belonged to the moderate wing of the Church of Scotland, and the fact that he received the Snell Exhibition suggests that he may have gone to Oxford with the intention of pursuing a career in the Church of England.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] The British economist Ronald Coase challenged the view that Smith was a deist, based on the fact that Smith's writings never explicitly invoke God as an explanation of the harmonies of the natural or the human worlds.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] Philosophy afterwards endeavoured to account for them, from more familiar causes, or from such as mankind were better acquainted with than the agency of the gods".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] Some authors argue that Smith's social and economic philosophy is inherently theological and that his entire model of social order is logically dependent on the notion of God's action in nature.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] Brendan Long argues that Smith was a theist, whereas according to Gavin Kennedy, Smith was "in some sense" a Christian.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] Smith was also a close friend of David Hume, who, despite debate about his religious views in modern scholarship, was commonly characterised in his own time as an atheist.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] The publication in 1777 of Smith's letter to William Strahan, in which he described Hume's courage in the face of death in spite of his irreligiosity, attracted considerable controversy.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] In 1759 Smith published his first work, *The Theory of Moral Sentiments,* sold by the co-publishers Andrew Millar of London and Alexander Kincaid of Edinburgh.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] Smith continued making extensive revisions to the book until his death.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] Although *The Wealth of Nations* is widely regarded as Smith's most influential work, Smith himself is believed to have considered *The Theory of Moral Sentiments* to be a superior work.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] Smith proposes a theory of sympathy, in which the act of observing others and seeing the judgements they form of both others and oneself makes people aware of themselves and how others perceive their behaviour.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] The feedback received by an individual from perceiving (or imagining) others' judgement creates an incentive to achieve "mutual sympathy of sentiments" with them and leads people to develop habits, and then principles, of behaviour, which come to constitute one's conscience.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] While scholars have historically recognised a conflict - often phrased the "Adam Smith Problem"-between the exaggeration on sympathy in *The Theory of Moral Sentiments* and self-interest in *The Wealth of Nations*, modern scholarship largely overlooks this contradiction.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] Instead the two works are widely seen as part of a unified system of moral and economic philosophy that are able to co-exist and complement each other.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] These scholars contend that in *The Theory of Moral Sentiments*, Smith develops a theory of psychology in which individuals seek the approval of the "impartial spectator" as a result of a natural desire to have outside observers sympathise with their sentiments.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] Rather than viewing *The Theory of Moral Sentiments* and *The Wealth of Nations* as presenting incompatible views of human nature, some Smith scholars regard the works as emphasising different aspects of human nature that vary depending on the situation.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] In the first part – *The Theory of Moral Sentiments* – he laid down the foundation of his vision of humanity and society.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] In the second – *The Wealth of Nations* – he elaborated on the virtue of prudence, which for him meant the relations between people in the private sphere of the economy.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] It was his plan to further elaborate on the virtue of justice in the third book.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] James Otteson argues that both books are Newtonian in their methodology and deploy a similar "market model" for explaining the creation and development of large-scale human social orders, including morality, economics, as well as language.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] Disagreement exists between classical and neoclassical economists about the central message of Smith's most influential work: *An Inquiry into the Nature and Causes of the Wealth of Nations* (1776).
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] He elaborated on the virtue of prudence, which for him meant the relations between people in the private sphere of the economy.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] He planned to further elaborate on the virtue of justice in the third book.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] Smith used the term "the invisible hand" in "History of Astronomy" referring to "the invisible hand of Jupiter", and once in each of his *The Theory of Moral Sentiments* (1759) and *The Wealth of Nations* (1776).
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] This last statement about "an invisible hand" has been interpreted in numerous ways.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] In relation to Bernard Mandeville's contention that "Private Vices ... may be turned into Public Benefits", Smith's belief that when an individual pursues his self-interest under conditions of justice, he unintentionally promotes the good of society.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] Self-interested competition in the free market, he argued, would tend to benefit society as a whole by keeping prices low, while still building in an incentive for a wide variety of goods and services.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] Smith states that the interest of manufacturers and merchants "in any particular branch of trade or manufactures, is always in some respects different from, and even opposite to, that of the public ...
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] The neoclassical interest in Smith's statement about "an invisible hand" originates in the possibility of seeing it as a precursor of neoclassical economics and its concept of general equilibrium; Paul Samuelson's "Economics" refers six times to Smith's "invisible hand".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] To emphasise this connection, Samuelson quotes Smith's "invisible hand" statement substituting "general interest" for "public interest".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] Samuelson concludes: "Smith was unable to prove the essence of his invisible-hand doctrine.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] Conversely, classical economists see in Smith's first sentences his programme to promote "The Wealth of Nations".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] Using the physiocratical concept of the economy as a circular process, to secure growth the inputs of Period 2 must exceed the inputs of Period 1.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] Therefore, those outputs of Period 1 which are not used or usable as inputs of Period 2 are regarded as unproductive labour, as they do not contribute to growth.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] This is what Smith had heard in France from, among others, François Quesnay, whose ideas Smith was so impressed by that he might have dedicated *The Wealth of Nations* to him had he not died beforehand.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] To this French insight that unproductive labour should be reduced to use labour more productively, Smith added his own proposal, that productive labour should be made even more productive by deepening the division of labour.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] Smith argued that deepening the division of labour under competition leads to greater productivity, which leads to lower prices and thus an increasing standard of living—"general plenty" and "universal opulence"—for all.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] Extended markets and increased production lead to the continuous reorganisation of production and the invention of new ways of producing, which in turn lead to further increased production, lower prices, and improved standards of living.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] Smith's central message is, therefore, that under dynamic competition, a growth machine secures "The Wealth of Nations".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] Smith's argument predicted Britain's evolution as the workshop of the world, underselling and outproducing all its competitors.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] According to Smith, "It is not very unreasonable that the rich should contribute to the public expense, not only in proportion to their revenue, but something more in that proportion".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] Smith wrote that a government is duty-bound to provide public services that "support the whole of society" like provide public education, transportation, national defence, a justice system, public safety, and public infrastructure to support commerce.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] Shortly before his death, Smith had nearly all his manuscripts destroyed.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] In his last years, he seemed to have been planning two major treatises, one on the theory and history of law and one on the sciences and arts.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] The posthumously published *Essays on Philosophical Subjects*, a history of astronomy down to Smith's own era, plus some thoughts on ancient physics and metaphysics, probably contain parts of what would have been the latter treatise.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] *Lectures on Jurisprudence* were notes taken from Smith's early lectures, plus an early draft of *The Wealth of Nations*, published as part of the 1976 Glasgow Edition of the works and correspondence of Smith.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p01] Other works, including some published posthumously, include *Lectures on Justice, Police, Revenue, and Arms* (1763) (first published in 1896); and *Essays on Philosophical Subjects* (1795).
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] In light of the arguments put forward by Smith and other economic theorists in Britain, academic belief in mercantilism began to decline in Britain in the late 18th century.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] During the Industrial Revolution, Britain embraced free trade and Smith's *laissez-faire* economics, and via the British Empire, used its power to spread a broadly liberal economic model around the world, characterised by open markets, and relatively barrier-free domestic and international trade.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] George Stigler attributes to Smith "the most important substantive proposition in all of economics".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] It is that, under competition, owners of resources (for example labour, land, and capital) will use them most profitably, resulting in an equal rate of return in equilibrium for all uses, adjusted for apparent differences arising from such factors as training, trust, hardship, and unemployment.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] Paul Samuelson finds in Smith's pluralist use of supply and demand as applied to wages, rents, and profit a valid and valuable anticipation of the general equilibrium modelling of Léon Walras a century later.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] Smith's allowance for wage increases in the short and intermediate term from capital accumulation and invention contrasted with Thomas Robert Malthus, David Ricardo, and Karl Marx in their propounding a rigid subsistence–wage theory of labour supply.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] Joseph Schumpeter criticised Smith for a lack of technical rigour, yet he argued that this enabled Smith's writings to appeal to wider audiences: "His very limitation made for success.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] Had he been more brilliant, he would not have been taken so seriously.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] Had he dug more deeply, had he unearthed more recondite truth, had he used more difficult and ingenious methods, he would not have been understood.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] But he had no such ambitions; in fact he disliked whatever went beyond plain common sense.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] He never moved above the heads of even the dullest readers.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] Classical economists presented competing theories to those of Smith, termed the "labour theory of value".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] Later Marxian economics descending from classical economics also use Smith's labour theories, in part.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] The first volume of Marx's major work, *Das Kapital*, was published in German in 1867.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] In it Marx focused on the labour theory of value and what he considered to be the exploitation of labour by capital.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] The labour theory of value held that the value of a thing was determined by the labour that went into its production.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] This contrasts with the modern contention of neoclassical economics, that the value of a thing is determined by what one is willing to give up to obtain the thing.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] Frédéric Bastiat advocated a similar theory, that the value of a thing or service was its utility, or usefulness, to others.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] One example he used was of one finding a large diamond after having done little labor; yet it was still valuable because others wanted it.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] The body of theory later termed "neoclassical economics" or "marginalism" formed from about 1870 to 1910.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] The term "economics" was popularised by such neoclassical economists as Alfred Marshall as a concise synonym for "economic science" and a substitute for the earlier, broader term "political economy" used by Smith.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] This corresponded to the influence on the subject of mathematical methods used in the natural sciences.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] Neoclassical economics systematised supply and demand as joint determinants of price and quantity in market equilibrium, affecting both the allocation of output and the distribution of income.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] It dispensed with the labour theory of value of which Smith was most famously identified with in classical economics, in favour of a marginal utility theory of value on the demand side and a more general theory of costs on the supply side.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] The bicentennial anniversary of the publication of *The Wealth of Nations* was celebrated in 1976, resulting in increased interest for *The Theory of Moral Sentiments* and his other works throughout academia.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] After 1976 Smith was more likely to be represented as the author of both *The Wealth of Nations* and *The Theory of Moral Sentiments*, and thereby as the founder of a moral philosophy and the science of economics.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] His *homo economicus* or "economic man" was also more often represented as a moral person.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] Additionally, economists David Levy and Sandra Peart in "The Secret History of the Dismal Science" point to his opposition to hierarchy and beliefs in equality, including racial equality, and provide additional support for those who point to Smith's opposition to slavery, colonialism, and empire.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] Emphasised also are Smith's statements of the need for high wages for the poor, and the efforts to keep wages low.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] They also cite Smith's opposition to the often expressed view that science is superior to common sense.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] He challenged ideas that colonies were key to British prosperity and power.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] He rejected that other cultures, such as China and India, were culturally and developmentally inferior to Europe.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] While he favoured "commercial society", he did not support radical social change and the imposition of commercial society on other societies.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] He proposed that colonies be given independence or that full political rights be extended to colonial subjects.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] Smith's chapter on colonies, in turn, would help shape British imperial debates from the mid-19th century onward.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] *The Wealth of Nations* would become an ambiguous text regarding the imperial question.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] In his chapter on colonies, Smith pondered how to solve the crisis developing across the Atlantic among the empire's 13 American colonies.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] He offered two different proposals for easing tensions.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] The first proposal called for giving the colonies their independence, and by thus parting on a friendly basis, Britain would be able to develop and maintain a free-trade relationship with them, and possibly even an informal military alliance.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] Smith's second proposal called for a theoretical imperial federation that would bring the colonies and the metropole closer together through an imperial parliamentary system and imperial free trade.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] Smith's most prominent disciple in 19th-century Britain, the peace-advocate Richard Cobden, preferred the first proposal.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] Cobden would lead the Anti-Corn Law League in overturning the Corn Laws in 1846, shifting Britain to a policy of free trade and empire "on the cheap" for decades to come.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] This hands-off approach toward the British Empire would become known as Cobdenism or the Manchester School.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] By the turn of the century, however, advocates of Smith's second proposal such as Joseph Shield Nicholson would become ever more vocal in opposing Cobdenism, calling instead for imperial federation.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] As Marc-William Palen notes: "On the one hand, Adam Smith's late nineteenth and early twentieth-century Cobdenite adherents used his theories to argue for gradual imperial devolution and empire 'on the cheap'.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] Between 1867 and 1870, a statue of Smith was built into the outside wall of 6 Burlington Gardens, then the headquarters of the University of London (now home to the Royal Academy of Arts).
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] A large-scale memorial of Smith by Alexander Stoddart was unveiled on 4 July 2008 in Edinburgh.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] It is a 10-foot (3.0 m)-tall bronze sculpture and it stands above the Royal Mile outside St Giles' Cathedral in Parliament Square, near the Mercat cross.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] Sculptor Jim Sanborn has created multiple pieces which feature Smith's work.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] At Central Connecticut State University is *Circulating Capital*, a tall cylinder which features an extract from *The Wealth of Nations* on the lower half, and on the upper half, some of the same text, but represented in binary code.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] At the University of North Carolina at Charlotte, outside the Belk College of Business Administration, is *Adam Smith's Spinning Top*.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] Another Smith sculpture is at Cleveland State University.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] A bust of Smith is in the Hall of Heroes of the National Wallace Monument in Stirling.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] Five paving stones, displaying quotations from Smith's works, were unveiled in December 2023 on High Street in Glasgow.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] They were commissioned by the University of Glasgow to mark the 300th anniversary of Smith's birth.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] Adam Smith resided at Panmure House from 1778 to 1790.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] In 2008, the house was purchased by the Edinburgh Business School at Heriot-Watt University and funds were raised for its restoration.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] In 2018 it was formally opened as a study centre in Smith's honour.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] Other writers have argued that Smith's support for *laissez-faire* (which in French means leave alone) has been overstated.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] Herbert Stein wrote that the people who "wear an Adam Smith necktie" do it to "make a statement of their devotion to the idea of free markets and limited government", and that this misrepresents Smith's ideas.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] Stein writes that Smith "was not pure or doctrinaire about this idea.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] He viewed government intervention in the market with great skepticism...yet he was prepared to accept or propose qualifications to that policy in the specific cases where he judged that their net effect would be beneficial and would not undermine the basically free character of the system.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] He did not wear the Adam Smith necktie." In Stein's reading, *The Wealth of Nations* could justify the Food and Drug Administration, the Consumer Product Safety Commission, mandatory employer health benefits, environmentalism, and "discriminatory taxation to deter improper or luxurious behavior".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] Some commentators have argued that Smith's works show support for a progressive, not flat, income tax and that he specifically named taxes that he thought should be required by the state, among them luxury-goods taxes and tax on rent.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] Yet Smith argued for the "impossibility of taxing the people, in proportion to their economic revenue, by any capitation".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] Smith argued that taxes should principally go toward protecting "justice" and "certain publick institutions" that were necessary for the benefit of all of society, which could not be adequately provided by private enterprise.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] Additionally, Smith outlined the proper expenses of the government in *The Wealth of Nations, Book V, Ch.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] Included in his requirements of a government is to enforce contracts and provide justice system, grant patents and copy rights, provide public goods such as infrastructure, provide national defence, and regulate banking.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] The role of the government was to provide goods "of such a nature that the profit could never repay the expense to any individual" such as roads, bridges, canals, and harbours.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] He also encouraged invention and new ideas through his patent enforcement and support of infant industry monopolies.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] He supported partial public subsidies for elementary education, and he believed that competition among religious institutions would provide general benefit to the society.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] Finally, he outlined how the government should support the dignity of the monarch or chief magistrate, such that they are equal or above the public in fashion.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] He further stated that monarchs should be provided for in a greater fashion than magistrates of a republic because "we naturally expect more splendor in the court of a king than in the mansion-house of a doge".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] However, he added that in general, a retaliatory tariff "seems a bad method of compensating the injury done to certain classes of our people, to do another injury ourselves, not only to those classes, but to almost all the other classes of them".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] Economic historians such as Jacob Viner regard Smith as a strong advocate of free markets and limited government (what Smith called "natural liberty"), but not as a dogmatic supporter of *laissez-faire*.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] The economist Daniel Klein believes using the term "free-market economics" or "free-market economist" to identify the ideas of Smith is too general and slightly misleading.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] Klein offers six characteristics central to the identity of Smith's economic thought and argues that a new name is needed to give a more accurate depiction of the "Smithian" identity.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] The economist David Ricardo set straight some of the misunderstandings about Smith's thoughts on free market.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] Many continue to fall victim to the thinking that Smith was a free-market economist without exception, though he was not.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] Ricardo pointed out that Smith was in support of helping infant industries.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] Smith believed that the government should subsidise newly formed industry, but he did fear that when the infant industry grew into adulthood, it would be unwilling to surrender the government help.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] Smith also supported tariffs on imported goods to counteract an internal tax on the same good.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] Smith also fell to pressure in supporting some tariffs in support for national defence.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/adam-smith-p02] Some have also argued, Emma Rothschild among them, that Smith would have supported a minimum wage, although no direct textual evidence supports the claim.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/after-virtue] The book was first published in 1981 and has since gone through two subsequent editions, which have added to, but not changed, the original text.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/after-virtue] The second edition, published in 1984, adds a postscript replying to critics of the first edition; the third edition, published in 2007, contains a new prologue entitled "*After Virtue* After a Quarter of a Century".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/after-virtue] MacIntyre holds that *After Virtue* makes seven central claims.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/after-virtue] It begins with an allegory suggestive of the premise of the science-fiction novel *A Canticle for Leibowitz*: a world where all sciences have been dismantled quickly and almost entirely.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/after-virtue] MacIntyre asks what the sciences would look like if they were re-assembled from the remnants of scientific knowledge that survived the catastrophe.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/after-virtue] He claims that the new sciences, though superficially similar to the old, would in fact be devoid of real scientific content, because the key suppositions and attitudes would not be present.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/after-virtue] MacIntyre claims that this failure encompasses the work of many significant Enlightenment and post-Enlightenment moral philosophers, including Søren Kierkegaard, Karl Marx, Immanuel Kant, and David Hume.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/after-virtue] These philosophers "fail because of certain shared characteristics deriving from their highly specific historical background." That background is the Enlightenment's abandonment of Aristotelianism, and in particular the Aristotelian concept of teleology.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/after-virtue] Ancient and medieval ethics, argues MacIntyre, relied wholly on the teleological idea that human life had a proper end or character, and that human beings could not reach this natural end without preparation.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/after-virtue] Renaissance science rejected Aristotle's teleological physics as an incorrect and unnecessary account, which led Renaissance philosophy to make a similar rejection in the realm of ethics.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/after-virtue] But shorn of teleology, ethics as a body of knowledge was expurgated of its central content, and only remained as, essentially, a vocabulary list with few definitions and no context.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/after-virtue] With such an incomplete framework on which to base their moral understanding, the philosophers of the Enlightenment and their successors were doomed from the beginning.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/after-virtue] MacIntyre illustrates this point through an example of a people who, he argues, experienced a similar incoherence in their own moral and ethical tradition: the Polynesian people of the South Pacific and their taboos.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/after-virtue] King Kamehameha II removed the taboos of the people in order to modernize their society and met little if any resistance.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/after-virtue] The fact that Kamehameha II could abolish them so easily and without opposition is evidence, MacIntyre argues, of their incoherence.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/after-virtue] A similar incoherence, he argues, bedevils the ethical project since the Enlightenment.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/after-virtue] Another reason MacIntyre gives for the doomed nature of the Enlightenment is the fact that it ascribed moral agency to the individual.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/after-virtue] He claims this made morality no more than one man's opinion and, thus, philosophy became a forum of inexplicably subjective rules and principles.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/after-virtue] The failure of the Enlightenment Project, because of the abandonment of a teleological structure, is shown by the inadequacy of moral emotivism, which MacIntyre believes accurately reflects the state of modern morality.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/after-virtue] MacIntyre offers a critique of Friedrich Nietzsche, whom he calls the "King Kamehameha II of the European tradition," in reference to the Polynesian allegory above.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/after-virtue] The nineteenth-century critic who has most lastingly and profoundly influenced MacIntyre is not Nietzsche but Marx—indeed, *After Virtue* originates in MacIntyre's plans to write a book repairing the moral weaknesses of Marxism.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/after-virtue] His critique of capitalism, and its associated liberal ideology and bureaucratic state (including what, in *After Virtue*, he condemned as the state capitalism of the USSR) is not expressed in traditional Marxist terms.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/after-virtue] Instead, it is written as a defence of ordinary social "practices", and of the "goods internal to practices".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/after-virtue] Pursuit of these helps to give narrative structure and intelligibility to our lives, but these goods must be defended against their corruption by "institutions", which pursue such "external goods" as money, power and status (chapters 14–15).
[src:a-theory-of-justice/after-virtue] MacIntyre seeks to find an alternative to Nietzsche's philosophy and eventually concludes that only classic Aristotelian thought can hope to save Western humanity.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/after-virtue] While Nietzsche seems to include the Aristotelian ethics and politics in his attack on the "degenerate disguises of the will to power," MacIntyre claims that this cannot be done due to important differences between the structure and assumptions of Aristotelian and post-Enlightenment philosophy.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/after-virtue] MacIntyre opposes Nietzsche's return to the aristocratic ethics of Homeric Greece with the teleological approach to ethics pioneered by Aristotle.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/after-virtue] Nietzsche's critique of Enlightenment moral theory does not work against a teleological ethics.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/after-virtue] In the end, however, MacIntyre tells us that we are waiting not for Godot but for Benedict of Nursia.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/after-virtue] MacIntyre criticizes individualist political philosophy, such as John Rawls' *A Theory of Justice* and Robert Nozick's *Anarchy, State, and Utopia*.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/after-virtue] To MacIntyre, morals and virtues can only be comprehended through their relation to the community which they come from.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/after-virtue] Whereas Rawls tells us to conceive of justice through abstracting ourselves from who we are (through the veil of ignorance, for example) MacIntyre disagrees.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/after-virtue] Running throughout *After Virtue* is the belief that in order to comprehend who we are, we must understand where we come from.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/after-virtue] The critic George Scialabba found *After Virtue* to be a strong critique of modernity, but claimed that MacIntyre "faltered" at the conclusion of the argument, when he sketched the features of what virtuous life should be like in the conditions of modernity.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/after-virtue] In particular, Scialabba objected to MacIntyre's claim that the good life for human beings consists in contemplating the good life for human beings; Scialabba found this insufficient and anticlimactic.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/after-virtue] In a review for *Political Theory*, William E.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/after-virtue] Anthony Ellis, in the journal *Philosophy*, argued that MacIntyre's positive philosophical project is not explained as well as it could have been: it is "of daunting opacity, though tantalizingly interesting" but not given enough space in the book.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/after-virtue] Ellis also states that the discussion of Rawls and Nozick in *After Virtue* "is slight and assertive".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] Some scholars suggest that agrarianism espouses the superiority of rural society to urban society and the independent farmer as superior to the paid worker, and sees farming as a way of life that can shape the ideal social values.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] It stresses the superiority of a simpler rural life in comparison to the complexity of urban life.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] The philosophical roots of agrarianism include European and Chinese philosophers.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] The Chinese school of Agriculturalism (农家/農家) was a philosophy that advocated peasant utopian communalism and egalitarianism.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] In societies influenced by Confucianism that had as its foundation that humans are innately good, the farmer was considered an esteemed productive member of society, but merchants who made money were looked down upon.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] That influenced European intellectuals like François Quesnay, an avid Confucianist and advocate of China's agrarian policies, in forming the French agrarian philosophy of physiocracy.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] The physiocrats, along with the ideas of John Locke and the Romantic Era, formed the basis of modern European and American agrarianism.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] , du Pont advocated low tariffs and free trade.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] Physiocracy (French: *physiocratie*; from the Greek for "government of nature") is an economic theory developed by a group of 18th-century Age of Enlightenment French economists.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] They believed that the wealth of nations derived solely from the value of "land agriculture" or "land development" and that agricultural products should be highly priced.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] Their theories originated in France and were most popular during the second half of the 18th century.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] Physiocracy became one of the first well-developed theories of economics.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] François Quesnay (1694–1774), the Marquis de Mirabeau (1715–1789) and Anne-Robert-Jacques Turgot (1727–1781) dominated the movement, which immediately preceded the first modern school, classical economics, which began with the publication of Adam Smith's *The Wealth of Nations* in 1776.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] The physiocrats made a significant contribution in their emphasis on productive work as the source of national wealth.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] This contrasted with earlier schools, in particular mercantilism, which often focused on the ruler's wealth, accumulation of gold, or the balance of trade.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] For the physiocrats, however, only agricultural labor created this value in the products of society.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] All "industrial" and non-agricultural labors were "unproductive appendages" to agricultural labor.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] Quesnay was likely influenced by his medical training, particularly by the work of William Harvey who explained how blood flow and the circulatory system is vital to the human body; Quesnay held that the circulation of wealth was vital to the economy.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] Societies at the time were also overwhelmingly agrarian.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] This may be why they viewed agriculture as the primary source of a nation's wealth.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] This is an idea that Quesnay purported to demonstrate with data, comparing a workshop to a farm.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] He analyzed "how money flowed between the three classes of farmers, proprietors, and artisans, in the same mechanical way that blood flows between different organs" and claimed only the farm produced a surplus that added to the nation's wealth.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] Physiocrats viewed the production of goods and services as equivalent to the consumption of the agricultural surplus, since human or animal muscle provided the main source of power and all energy derived from the surplus from agricultural production.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] Profit in capitalist production was really only the "rent" obtained by the owner of the land on which the agricultural production took place.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] "The physiocrats damned cities for their artificiality and praised what they considered to be more natural styles of living.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] They celebrated farmers." They called themselves *les Économistes*, but are generally referred to as "physiocrats" to distinguish their beliefs from the many schools of economic thought that followed.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] The United States president Thomas Jefferson was an agrarian who based his ideas about the budding American democracy around the notion that farmers are "the most valuable citizens" and the truest republicans.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] Jefferson and his support base were committed to American republicanism, which they saw as being in opposition to monarchy, aristocracy, clericalism and corruption, and which prioritized morality and virtue, exemplified by the "yeoman farmer", "planters", and the "plain folk".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] In praising the rural farmfolk, the Jeffersonians felt that financiers, bankers and industrialists created "cesspools of corruption" in the cities and should thus be avoided.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] The Jeffersonians sought to align the American economy more with agriculture than industry.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] Part of their motive to do so was Jefferson's fear that the over-industrialization of America would create a class of wage slaves who relied on their employers for income and sustenance.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] In turn, these workers would cease to be independent voters as their vote could be manipulated by said employers.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] There is general agreement that the substantial United States' federal policy of offering land grants (such as thousands of gifts of land to veterans) had a positive impact on economic development in the 19th century.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] Agrarian socialism is a form of agrarianism that is anti-capitalist in nature and seeks to introduce socialist economic systems in their stead.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] One notable agrarian socialists was Emiliano Zapata, a leading figure in the Mexican Revolution.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] As the leader of the Liberation Army of the South, his group of revolutionaries fought on behalf of the Mexican peasants, whom they saw as exploited by the landowning classes.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] Zapata published the Plan of Ayala, which called for significant land reforms and land redistribution in Mexico as part of the revolution.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] Zapata was killed and his forces crushed over the course of the Revolution, but his political ideas lived on in the form of Zapatismo.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] Zapatismo would form the basis for neozapatismo, the ideology of the modern Zapatista Army of National Liberation.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] Known as *Ejército Zapatista de Liberación Nacional* or EZLN in Spanish, EZLN is a far-left, libertarian socialist political and militant group that emerged in the state of Chiapas in southmost Mexico in 1994.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] EZLN and Neozapatismo, as explicit in their name, seek to revive the agrarian socialist movement of Zapata, but fuse it with new elements such as a commitment to indigenous rights and community-level decision making.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] Maoism, the far-left ideology of Mao Zedong and his followers, places a heavy emphasis on the role of peasants in its goals.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] In contrast to other Marxist schools of thought which normally seek to acquire the support of urban workers, Maoism sees the peasantry as key.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] During the Chinese Civil War and the Second Sino-Japanese War, Mao and the Chinese Communist Party made extensive use of peasants and rural bases in their military tactics, often eschewing the cities.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] Following the eventual victory of the Communist Party in both wars, the countryside and how it should be run remained a focus for Mao.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] In 1958, Mao launched the Great Leap Forward, a social and economic campaign which, amongst other things, altered many aspects of rural Chinese life.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] It introduced mandatory collective farming and forced the peasantry to organize itself into communal living units which were known as people's communes.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] These communes, which consisted of 5,000 people on average, were expected to meet high production quotas while the peasants who lived on them adapted to this radically new way of life.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] The communes were run as co-operatives where wages and money were replaced by work points.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] Peasants who criticised this new system were persecuted as "rightists" and "counter-revolutionaries".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] Leaving the communes was forbidden and escaping from them was difficult or impossible, and those who attempted it were subjected to party-orchestrated "public struggle sessions," which further jeopardized their survival.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] These public criticism sessions were often used to intimidate the peasants into obeying local officials and they often devolved into little more than public beatings.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] On the communes, experiments were conducted in order to find new methods of planting crops, efforts were made to construct new irrigation systems on a massive scale, and the communes were all encouraged to produce steel backyard furnaces as part of an effort to increase steel production.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] Similarly, the experimentation with the crops did not produce results.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] In addition to this the Four Pests Campaign was launched, in which the peasants were called upon to destroy sparrows and other wild birds that ate crop seeds, in order to protect fields.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] Pest birds were shot down or scared away from landing until they dropped from exhaustion.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] This campaign resulted in an ecological disaster that saw an explosion of the vermin population, especially crop-eating insects, which was consequently not in danger of being killed by predators.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] None of these new systems were working, but local leaders did not dare to state this, instead, they falsified reports so as not to be punished for failing to meet the quotas.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] In many cases they stated that they were greatly exceeding their quotas, and in turn, the Chinese state developed a completely false sense of success with regard to the commune system.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] All of this culminated in the Great Chinese Famine, which began in 1959, lasted 3 years, and saw an estimated 15 to 30 million Chinese people die.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] A combination of bad weather and the new, failed farming techniques that were introduced by the state led to massive shortages of food.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] By 1962, the Great Leap Forward was declared to be at an end.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] In the late 1960s and early 1970s, Mao once again radically altered life in rural China with the launching of the Down to the Countryside Movement.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] As a response to the Great Chinese Famine, the Chinese President Liu Shaoqi began "sending down" urban youths to rural China in order to recover its population losses and alleviate overcrowding in the cities.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] However, Mao turned the practice into a political crusade, declaring that the sending down would strip the youth of any bourgeois tendencies by forcing them to learn from the unprivileged rural peasants.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] In reality, it was the Communist Party's attempt to reign in the Red Guards, who had become uncontrollable during the course of the Cultural Revolution.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] 10% of the 1970 urban population of China was sent out to remote rural villages, often in Inner Mongolia.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] The villages, which were still poorly recovering from the effects of the Great Chinese Famine, did not have the excess resources that were needed to support the newcomers.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] Furthermore, the so-called "sent-down youth" had no agricultural experience and as a result, they were unaccustomed to the harsh lifestyle that existed in the countryside, and their unskilled labor in the villages provided little benefit to the agricultural sector.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] As a result, many of the sent-down youth died in the countryside.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] The relocation of the youths was originally intended to be permanent, but by the end of the Cultural Revolution, the Communist Party relented and some of those who had the capacity to return to the cities were allowed to do so.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] In imitation of Mao's policies, the Khmer Rouge of Cambodia (who were heavily funded and supported by the People's Republic of China) created their own version of the Great Leap Forward which was known as "Maha Lout Ploh".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] With the Great Leap Forward as its model, it had similarly disastrous effects, contributing to what is now known as the Cambodian genocide.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] As a part of the Maha Lout Ploh, the Khmer Rouge sought to create an entirely agrarian socialist society by forcibly relocating 100,000 people to move from Cambodia's cities into newly created communes.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] The Khmer Rouge leader, Pol Pot sought to "purify" the country by setting it back to "Year Zero", freeing it from "corrupting influences".
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] Besides trying to completely de-urbanize Cambodia, ethnic minorities were slaughtered along with anyone else who was suspected of being a "reactionary" or a member of the "bourgeoisie", to the point that wearing glasses was seen as grounds for execution.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] The killings were only brought to an end when Cambodia was invaded by the neighboring socialist nation of Vietnam, whose army toppled the Khmer Rouge.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] However, with Cambodia's entire society and economy in disarray, including its agricultural sector, the country still plunged into renewed famine due to vast food shortages.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] However, as international journalists began to report on the situation and send images of it out to the world, a massive international response was provoked, leading to one of the most concentrated relief efforts of its time.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] Peasant parties first appeared across Eastern Europe between 1860 and 1910, when commercialized agriculture and world market forces disrupted traditional rural society, and the railway and growing literacy facilitated the work of roving organizers.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] Agrarian parties advocated land reforms to redistribute land on large estates among those who work it.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] They also wanted village cooperatives to keep the profit from crop sales in local hands and credit institutions to underwrite needed improvements.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] Many peasant parties were also nationalist parties because peasants often worked their land for the benefit of landlords of different ethnicity.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] Peasant parties rarely had any power before World War I but some became influential in the interwar era, especially in Bulgaria and Czechoslovakia.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] For a while, in the 1920s and the 1930s, there was a Green International (International Agrarian Bureau) based on the peasant parties in Bulgaria, Czechoslovakia, Poland, and Serbia.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] It functioned primarily as an information center that spread the ideas of agrarianism and combating socialism on the left and landlords on the right and never launched any significant activities.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] In Bulgaria, the Bulgarian Agrarian National Union (BZNS) was organized in 1899 to resist taxes and build cooperatives.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] BZNS came to power in 1919 and introduced many economic, social, and legal reforms.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] However, conservative forces crushed BZNS in a 1923 coup and assassinated its leader, Aleksandar Stamboliyski (1879–1923).
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] BZNS was made into a communist puppet group until 1989, when it reorganized as a genuine party.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] In Czechoslovakia, the Republican Party of Agricultural and Smallholder People often shared power in parliament as a partner in the five-party pětka coalition.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] The party's leader, Antonín Švehla (1873–1933), was prime minister several times.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] It was consistently the strongest party, forming and dominating coalitions.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] It moved beyond its original agrarian base to reach middle-class voters.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] The party was banned by the National Front after the Second World War.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] In France, the Hunting, Fishing, Nature, Tradition party is a moderate conservative, agrarian party, reaching a peak of 4.23% in the 2002 French presidential election.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] It would later on become affiliated to France's main conservative party, Union for a Popular Movement.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] More recently, the Resistons! movement of Jean Lassalle espoused agrarianism.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] In Hungary, the first major agrarian party, the small-holders party was founded in 1908.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] The party became part of the government in the 1920s but lost influence in the government.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] A new party, the Independent Smallholders, Agrarian Workers and Civic Party was established in 1930 with a more radical program representing larger scale land redistribution initiatives.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] They implemented this program together with the other coalition parties after WWII.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] However, after 1949 the party was outlawed when a one-party system was introduced.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] They became part of the government again 1990–1994, and 1998–2002 after which they lost political support.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] The ruling Fidesz party has an agrarian faction, and promotes agrarian interest since 2010 with the emphasis now placed on supporting larger family farms versus small-holders.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] In the late 19th century, the Irish National Land League aimed to abolish landlordism in Ireland and enable tenant farmers to own the land they worked on.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] The "Land War" of 1878–1909 led to the Irish Land Acts, ending absentee landlords and ground rent and redistributing land among peasant farmers.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] Post-independence, the Farmers' Party operated in the Irish Free State from 1922, folding into the National Centre Party in 1932.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] It was mostly supported by wealthy farmers in the east of Ireland.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] Clann na Talmhan (Family of the Land; also called the *National Agricultural Party*) was founded in 1938.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] They focused more on the poor smallholders of the west, supporting land reclamation, afforestation, social democracy and rates reform.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] They formed part of the governing coalition of the Government of the 13th Dáil and Government of the 15th Dáil.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] Economic improvement in the 1960s saw farmers vote for other parties and Clann na Talmhan disbanded in 1965.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] In Kazakhstan, the Peasants' Union, originally a communist organization, was formed as one of first agrarian parties in independent Kazakhstan and would win four seats in the 1994 legislative election.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] The Agrarian Party of Kazakhstan, led by Romin Madinov, was founded in 1999, which favored the privatization of agricultural land, developments towards rural infrastructure, as well as changes in the tax system in agrarian economy.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] From there, the bloc remained short-lived as it would merge with the ruling Nur Otan party in 2006.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] Several other parties in Kazakhstan over the years have embraced agrarian policies in their programs in an effort to appeal towards a large rural Kazakh demographic base, which included Amanat, ADAL, and Respublica.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] Since late 2000s, the Auyl party remains the largest and most influential agrarian-oriented party in Kazakhstan, as its presidential candidate Jiguli Dairabaev had become the second-place frontrunner in the 2022 presidential election after sweeping 3.4% of the vote.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] In the 2023 legislative election, the Auyl party for the first time was represented the parliament after winning nine seats in the lower chamber Mäjilis.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] The party raises rural issues in regard to decaying villages, rural development and the agro-industrial complex, the issues of social security of the rural population, and has consistently opposed the ongoing rural flight in Kazakhstan.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] In Latvia, the Union of Greens and Farmers is supportive of traditional small farms and perceives them as more environmentally friendly than large-scale farming: Nature is threatened by development, while small farms are threatened by large industrial-scale farms.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] In Lithuania, the government led by the Lithuanian Farmers and Greens Union was in power between 2016 and 2020.
[src:a-theory-of-justice/agrarianism] The Nordic agrarian parties, also referred to as Scandinavian agrarian parties or agrarian liberal parties, are agrarian political parties that belong to a political tradition particular to the Nordic countries.
